<BLOCK1><TI>CLAIM</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff, Aviva Canada Inc., claims:
<P1>a. damages for fraudulent misrepresentation, breach of the duty of honest performance of a contract, unjust enrichment, and conspiracy to commit fraud, in the amount of $10,017.86 as against the Defendants;</P1>
<P1>b. damages for trespass to property in the amount of $20,000 as against the Defendants 1843538 Ontario Inc. carrying on business as Mississauga Collision Centre and/or McLaren Collision, Rony Amanuel Warda, and Fady Rony Warda;</P1>
<P1>c. damages in the amount of $100,000 for investigative costs, as against all Defendants;</P1>
<P1>d. punitive and exemplary damages in the sum of $200,000, as against all Defendants;</P1>
<P1>e. prejudgment and post-judgment interest pursuant to the Courts of Justice Act, R.S.O. 1990, c, C.43, as against all Defendants;</P1>
<P1>f. costs of this action on a substantial indemnity basis, including HST, as against all Defendants; and</P1>
<P1>g. such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>THE PARTIES</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>THE PLAINTIFF</TI>
<P>2. The Plaintiff, Aviva Canada Inc. (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;), is an insurance company duly incorporated and licensed by the laws of Ontario to carry on business as an automobile insurer. Aviva's head office is located in the City of Markham, in the Province of Ontario.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>THE DEFENDANTS</TI>
<P>3. The Defendant, 1843538 Ontario Inc. is a duly incorporated company which carries on business, under the firm name and style of Mississauga Auto Collision Centre, and/or McLaren Collision (hereinafter known as &ldquo;McLaren&rdquo;), as an auto body shop located at 1095 Fewster Drive in Mississauga, Ontario.</P>
<P>4. The Defendant, Rony Amanuel Warda (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Rony Warda&rdquo;), resides in Milton and/or Mississauga and is the named owner of McLaren.</P>
<P>5. The Defendant, Fady Rony Warda (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Fady Warda&rdquo;), resides in Milton and was at all material times an employee of McLaren.</P>
<P>6. The Defendant, Michael Wetzel (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Michael Wetzel&rdquo;), resides in Markham and at all material times was employed as a Senior Auto Damage Appraiser by Aviva.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>THE NATURE OF THIS ACTION</TI>
<P>7. This action arises out of the Defendants' conspiracy to defraud Aviva through a series of fraudulent misrepresentations and unlawful actions in relation to repairs made to two motor vehicles, a 2010 Ford Fusion (hereinafter known as &ldquo;the Fusion&rdquo;) and a 2016 Chrysler 200 (hereinafter known as &ldquo;the Chrysler&rdquo;), owned by Aviva. The material events took place in May of 2017 and September/October of 2017 respectively.</P>
<P>8. In 2017 Aviva was studying the auto collision repair industry in the Greater Toronto Area. Aviva purchased the Fusion and the Chrysler and then damaged the vehicles in a controlled setting. The vehicles were then appraised by an independent appraiser and taken to McLaren to have the damages appraised and repaired in the normal course of an insurance claim.</P>
<P>9. The Fusion and the Chrysler were taken to McLaren in May of 2017 and September/October of 2017 respectively. They were each appraised by Michael Wetzel of Aviva after which time they were purportedly repaired. Upon completion of the repairs, the vehicles were appraised once again by an independent appraiser, at Aviva's request. Fraudulent misrepresentations were identified in the appraisal completed by Michael Wetzel. Fraudulent misrepresentations were also identified in the invoices submitted by McLaren and Rony Warda.</P>
<P>10. Furthermore, it became known that Fady Warda deliberately caused damage to the Fusion by striking it violently and repeatedly with an object with the intent to cause farther damage and inflate the repair costs. This deliberate act was carried out in the presence of, and with the knowledge of, Michael Wetzel.</P>
<P>11. It also became known that Rony Warda deliberately caused damage to the Chrysler by striking it violently and repeatedly with an object with the intent to cause further damage and inflate the repair costs. This deliberate act was carried out in the presence of, and with the knowledge of, Michael Wetzel.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>THE FRAUDULENT ACTS</TI>
<P>12. As described above, Aviva ascertained that there were fraudulent misrepresentations made in regards to the appraisals submitted by Michael Wetzel, as well as fraudulent misrepresentations made in the invoices submitted by McLaren and Rony Warda regarding the repairs completed to the vehicles in question.</P>
<P>13. In particular, it became clear to Aviva that, in regards to the appraisals completed by Michael Wetzel:
<P1>a. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts were included on the appraisal as being required to be replaced which in fact were not damaged and did not need to be replaced;</P1>
<P1>b. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts were included on the appraisal as requiring refinishing when in fact they were not damaged and did not require refinishing.</P1>
<P1>c. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts were listed on the appraisal to be replaced and/or refinished which had not initially been damaged prior to the vehicle being taken to McLaren, but were deliberately damaged by Fady Warda and Rony Warda, with the knowledge of all other Defendants.</P1></P>
<P>14. In regards to the purported repairs to the vehicles, Aviva became aware that:
<P1>a. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts on the vehicles were intentionally damaged by Fady Warda and Rony Warda and then repaired and invoiced;</P1>
<P1>b. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts were reported to have been replaced but were not replaced yet invoiced; and</P1>
<P1>c. to the knowledge of the Defendants, various parts were reported to have been repaired but were not repaired yet invoiced.</P1></P>
<P>15. An employment agreement existed between Aviva and Michael Wetzel whereby the said Defendant agreed to perform appraisal services for Aviva in accordance with Aviva's Code of Conduct. It was an express term of the Code of Conduct that Michael Wetzel would perform the appraisals honestly and not participate in any fraudulent activity with an auto body shop in relation to the appraisals completed.</P>
<P>16. Furthermore, each time an auto body shop, such as McLaren, agrees with an insurer, such as Aviva, to carry out repairs to an insured's vehicle, a contract is created in which the auto body shop agrees to perform the repairs completely and honestly and the insurer agrees to pay the appropriate price for the work. Such contracts existed in the case of the Fusion and the Chrysler.</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>FRAUD &amp; FRAUDULENT MISREPRESENTATION</TI>
<P>17. As particularized above, the Defendants together and in concert designed, orchestrated and implemented a scheme to defraud Aviva and thereby obtain monies from Aviva under false pretences.</P>
<P>18. The Defendants made false representations, knowingly, without belief in their truth, or recklessly, careless as to whether the representations were true or false. The Defendants intended that Aviva should act in reliance on the representations and Aviva has suffered damages as a result of such reliance.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>BREACH OF DUTY OF GOOD FAITH/BREACH OF DUTY OF HONEST PERFORMANCE</TI>
<P>19. The Defendants committed the tort of breach of duty of good faith in that they owed a duty to act honestly in the performance of contractual obligations and they failed to do so as described above.</P>
<P>20. The Defendants also failed to fulfil their duty of honest performance in contractual relations.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>CONSPIRACY</TI>
<P>21. The Defendants committed the tort of conspiracy in that:
<P1>a. the conduct of the Defendants was unlawful, planned and deliberate, was directed towards Aviva, and the Defendants knew, or should have known, in the circumstances that injury to Aviva was likely to, and did, result;</P1>
<P1>b. in the alternative, and in addition to (a.), the means planned, coordinated and agreed upon between and among the Defendants were both lawful and unlawful but the predominant purpose of the Defendants' conduct was to cause injury to Aviva and such injury did result.</P1></P>
<P>22. The Defendants agreed, or had a common intention, to pursue a course of action which has resulted in damage to Aviva. The Defendants committed overt acts referred to above in pursuance of their common design.</P>
<P>23. The acts and means by which the Defendants agreement was carried into effect were unlawful and were directed at Aviva. These acts included fraud and deceit resulting in the damages that Aviva has sustained.</P>
<P>24. Insofar as lawful means were used by the Defendants to achieve the object of the conspiracy, the Defendants intended to injure Aviva.</P>
<P>25. Aviva's damages are causally related to the acts taken pursuant to the agreement among the Defendants.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>UNJUST ENRICHMENT</TI>
<P>26. The Defendants received a benefit as a result of their fraudulent actions while Aviva suffered a loss in direct relation to the benefit gained by the Defendants. There was also no legally justified reason for the benefit sustained by the Defendants resulting in the loss suffered by Aviva.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>TRESPASS TO PROPERTY</TI>
<P>27. Fady Warda and Rony Warda committed the act of trespass to property in that they intentionally vandalised the Fusion and the Chrysler when they were not acting under a right or authority conferred by law to do so, and they did not have the express permission of Aviva to engage in such an activity, which was prohibited.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>PUNITIVE DAMAGES</TI>
<P>28. The conduct of the Defendants is such as to justify an award of punitive and/or exemplary damages. The Defendants have behaved with arrogance and high-handedness, have shown a callous disregard and complete lack of concern for Aviva's rights and ought to be punished and deterred from this sort of misconduct. The Defendants' conduct was sufficiently reprehensible so as to justify an award of punitive and/or exemplary damages from the Defendants. The Defendants were aware of the probable consequences of their conduct and the damage such conduct would cause Aviva.</P>
<P>29. The Defendants' conduct was high-handed, reckless, without cause, deliberate, and in disregard of Aviva. They knew or ought to have known that their actions and omissions would have a significant adverse effect on Aviva.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>PLACE OF TRIAL</TI>
<P>The Plaintiff proposes that this action be tried at the City of Toronto in the Province of Ontario.</P>
