<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONSE TO THE FRAUD ALLEGATIONS</TI>
<P>11. First, contrary to what has been alleged by the plaintiff Aviva, the defendant Wetzel pleads, and the fact is, that at no time did he ever conspire with any of the other defendants to defraud or otherwise harm the plaintiff in any way, shape or form.</P>
<P>12. Second, contrary to what has been alleged by the plaintiff Aviva, the defendant Wetzel pleads, and the fact is, that at no time did he ever witness or have any knowledge of any deliberate acts of damage done to the subject vehicles while they were being repaired at the McLaren Collision Centre.</P>
<P>13. Third, contrary to what has been alleged by the plaintiff Aviva, the defendant Wetzel pleads, and the fact is, that at no time did he ever receive any kind of monetary compensation, either in the form of a &ldquo;kickback&rdquo; or otherwise, from any of the other defendants. Rather, at all times, Wetzel's only monetary compensation for the two subject appraisals performed was his usual employment income from Aviva, and nothing else.</P>
<P>14. Fourth, it is important to note that the defendant Wetzel's scope of employment was limited solely to that of an appraiser. In particular, it was <UNDER>not</UNDER> within the scope of his employment duties as an appraiser to subsequently verify if the body shop actually performed the services that it had billed for. Thus, none of the foregoing discrepancies mentioned in the two charts between what was billed by the body shop and what was allegedly performed bears any relevance to the defendant Wetzel.</P>
<P>15. Finally, there are a number of fundamental defects in the way that Aviva conducted its appraisals of the subject vehicles which explain, either in whole or in part, the noted discrepancies between Wetzel's appraisals and Clark's appraisals. These defects are as follows:
<P1>(i) In neither of the Ford or the Chrysler vehicles did Aviva's appraiser perform a &ldquo;tear down&rdquo; of the vehicles prior to them being sent to the shop for repair. This defect is fundamental because it is only with the benefit of a such a &ldquo;tear down&rdquo;, where the interior of the vehicle can be examined, that the appraiser can fully understand the extent of any damage caused to the vehicle. In direct contrast to the Clark appraisals, Wetzel did have the benefit of full &ldquo;tear downs&rdquo; prior to the repairs, where he was able to properly ascertain the true extent of the damage done to the vehicles;</P1>
<P1>(ii) Clark, as Aviva's selected appraiser, failed to use a paint gauge before and after the vehicles were repaired. This is also fundamental because it is only through this technology that an appraiser can verify whether or not the vehicle has been painted over from its original painting;</P1>
<P1>(iii) Clark, as Aviva's selected appraiser, failed to take unibody measurements before and after the repairs. This is a fundamental error since it is only with such measurements that one can properly ascertain whether any deformation to the unibody of the vehicle has occurred. This failure alone is sufficient to negate the findings of Aviva's appraiser; and</P1>
<P1>(iv) Finally, Aviva's selected appraiser also failed to perform any alignment specifications before and after the repairs. This failure is also fatal to Aviva's claim of fraudulent discrepancies between Wetzel's and Clark's appraisals.</P1></P>
<P>16. As is clear from the foregoing, the noted discrepancies between the Clark appraisals and the Wetzel appraisals is merely a reflection of the different methodologies employed by the two men. In other words, had Clark, as Aviva's appraiser, properly conducted the foregoing tests, including the all-important unibody measurements, the noted discrepancies would likely disappear. In any event, what is clear and undeniable is that Aviva's noted discrepancies have nothing to do with any fraudulent intent on the part of the defendant Wetzel, but rather reflect a legitimate and honest difference of opinion arising from the different methodologies used.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>AVIVA'S VIOLATIONS OF FEDERAL CRIMINAL LAW</TI>
<P>17. By virtue of the fact that Aviva has admitted to staging fake car accidents, the focus of inquiry shifts to whether such actions, in and of themselves, violate federal criminal law. The defendant Wetzel pleads, and the fact is, that the answer to that question is unquestionably &ldquo;ye s&rdquo;.</P>
<P>18. In the case at bar, it is undeniable that Aviva has committed the criminal offence of mischief, which is defined as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>430.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Every one commits mischief who wilfully
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>destroys or damages property;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>renders property dangerous, useless, inoperative or ineffective;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>obstructs, interrupts or interferes with the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(d)</N><PARAP>obstructs, interrupts or interferes with any person in the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>429.</N><SSEC><N>(3)</N><SSECP>Where it is an offence to destroy or to damage anything,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the fact that a person has a partial interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage; and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the fact that a person has a total interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage with intent to defraud.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. In the case at bar, and contrary to what has been alleged by the plaintiff Aviva, <UNDER>none</UNDER> of the damaged cars were owned by Aviva. Accordingly, the admitted fact that Aviva deliberately damaged the cars in question necessarily means that it has committed the criminal offence of mischief.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>AVIVA'S VIOLATIONS OF PROVINCIAL INSURANCE LAW</TI>
<P>20. Subsection 233(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. I.8, as amended, reads as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>233.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Where,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>an applicant for a contract,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>gives false particulars of the described automobile to be insured to the prejudice of the insurer, or</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(ii)</N><SPARAP>knowingly misrepresents or fails to disclose in the application any fact required to be stated therein;</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the insured contravenes a term of the contract or commits a fraud; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>the insured wilfully makes a false statement in respect of a claim under the contract,</PARAP></PARA>
a claim by the insured is invalid and the right of the insured to recover indemnity is forfeited.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>21. In the case at bar, both insureds, after the &ldquo;accidents&rdquo; in question had occurred, wilfully made false statements in respect of their claims to Aviva since they knew that no &ldquo;accident&rdquo; had in fact occurred and that the whole thing was staged. Accordingly, pursuant to subsections 233(1)(b) and (c) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, each insureds contract of insurance with Aviva was rendered &ldquo;invalid&rdquo;, and their right to recover indemnity from the insurer Aviva was &ldquo;forfeited.&rdquo; Accordingly, since Aviva paid insurance under &ldquo;forfeited&rdquo; contracts, it can &ldquo;recover&rdquo; its losses by claiming back as against the insureds themselves.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>AVIVA'S ACTION BARRED BY THE DOCTRINE OF <EM>EX TURPI CAUSA NON ORITUR ACTIO</EM></TI>
<P>22. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 4</CITE></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada (per Rothstein, J.) ruled as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[20] The question is, &ldquo;under what circumstances should the immoral or criminal conduct of a plaintiff bar the plaintiff from recovering damages to which he or she would otherwise be entitled&rdquo; (p. 169). The following principles and approach are established in <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC></CASEREF> and are applicable in the present case.</P>
<P>1. Application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine in the tort context invalidates otherwise valid and enforceable actions in tort (p. 169).</P>
<P>2. Therefore, its application must be based on a firm doctrinal foundation and be made subject to clear limits and should occur &ldquo;in very limited circumstances&rdquo; (p. 169).</P>
<P>3. The only justification for its application is the preservation of the integrity of the legal system. This concern is only in issue where a damage award in a civil suit would allow a person to profit from illegal or wrongful conduct or would permit evasion or rebate of a penalty prescribed by the criminal law (p. 169).
<QUOTE><P>It would, in short, introduce an inconsistency in the law. It is particularly important in this context that we bear in mind that the law must aspire to be a unified institution, the parts of which&mdash;contract, tort, the criminal law&mdash;must be in essential harmony. For the courts to punish conduct with the one hand while rewarding it with the other, would be to &ldquo;create an intolerable fissure in the law's conceptually seamless web&rdquo;: Weinrib, <EM>supra</EM>, at p. 42. We thus see that the concern, put at its most fundamental, is with the integrity of the legal system. [p. 176]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>4. The <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine generally does not preclude an award of damages in tort because such awards tend to compensate the plaintiff rather than amount to &ldquo;profit&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>Such damages accomplish nothing more than to put the plaintiff in the position he or she would have been in had the tort not occurred. . . . [A plaintiff should get] only the value of, or a substitute for, the injuries he or she has suffered by the fault of another. <UNDER>He or she gets nothing for or by reason of the fact he or she was</UNDER> <UNDER>engaged in illegal conduct.</UNDER> [pp. 176-77]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>5. The <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is a defence in a tort action. The plaintiff's illegal conduct does not give rise to a judicial discretion to negate or refuse to consider the duty of care which goes to the relationship between a plaintiff and a defendant. It is independent of that relationship. The defendant may have caused harm by acting wrongly or negligently, but the &ldquo;responsibility for this wrong is suspended only because concern for the integrity of the legal system trumps the concern that the defendant be responsible&rdquo; (pp. 181-82).</P>
<P>6. Treating the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine as a defence places the onus on the defendant to prove the illegal or immoral conduct that precludes the plaintiff's action. And as a defence, it allows for segregation between claims for personal injury and claims that would constitute profit from illegal or immoral conduct or the evasion of or a rebate of a penalty provided by the criminal law.</P></QUOTE>
(Emphasis added.) Accordingly, since all of the compensatory damages that are being claimed by the plaintiff were <UNDER>directly</UNDER> caused by the criminal and illegal mischief that it engaged in by deliberately damaging the vehicles in question, Aviva should &ldquo;get nothing&rdquo; in damages on account thereof. Thus, by its very nature, this action is indeed an abuse of the process of the Court, and should be summarily dismissed on account thereof.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>23. The plaintiff Aviva is in the business of selling insurance, including automobile insurance, to the general public throughout this province. No one questions that this company, like any other insurer, is free to investigate fraud throughout the auto body repair industry, including any fraud that arises in relation thereto from within its own ranks. However, this freedom to investigate and, if any fraud is indeed discovered, to prosecute such fraud in the civil context is premised on there being actual fraud out there directed as against itself. It does not, however, extend t o situations such as the one at bar whereby Aviva itself fabricated fake accidents in the hope of catching would -be fraudsters in the act. By so doing, Aviva committed the criminal offence of mischief by deliberately damaging vehicles that it did not own itself. Even assuming, in <EM>arguendo</EM>, that the defendant Wetzel did commit fraudulent conduct (which is of course denied), Aviva's claim as against him is foreclosed by the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>. Simply put, Aviva cannot profit from its own criminal wrongdoing. In any event, and as has been explained herein, the defendant Wetzel committed no fraud and breached no duty to Aviva, whether in contract, in tort, fiduciary, or otherwise, and thus cannot be held liable in any way to Aviva. Thus, the action as against himself must be dismissed, with costs in his favour on a substantial indemnity basis.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">COUNTERCLAIM</TI>
<P>24. The defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) Wetzel claims as against the plaintiff (defendant by counterclaim) Aviva as follows:
<P1>(i) Compensatory damages, including moral damages, together with all outstanding statutory severance, termination and vacation pay, collectively in the amount of $750,000, all arising out of Aviva's unlawful termination of Wetzel's contract of employment therewith;</P1>
<P1>(ii) Punitive damages in the amount of $250,000 on account of Aviva's breach of its duty of good faith conduct in the manner that it terminated its employment of Wetzel;</P1>
<P1>(iii) Pre-judgment and post-judgment interest on the amounts claimed at the rates provided for in the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43, as amended;</P1>
<P1>(iv) Cost of this counterclaim on a substantial indemnity basis;</P1>
<P1>(v) HST where applicable to those amounts awarded by this Court; and</P1>
<P1>(vi) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Court deems just and appropriate.</P1></P>
<P>25. The defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) repeats, relies and incorporates herein all of the allegations made in paras. 1 to 23 (both inclusive) of his statement of defence.</P>
<P>26. Wetzel is a 59 year-old man whose career as an appraiser in the automobile industry has been destroyed on account of the false fraud allegations that have been leveled against him by Aviva. Accordingly, Wetzel seeks to collect on what would have been his future employment income from Aviva until his retirement at the age of 65.</P>
