<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;STATEMENT OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Striking Pleadings</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Law and Analysis as Applied to the Case at Bar</EM></TI>
<BLOCK5><TI><EM>Rule 21.01</EM></TI>
<P>10. Rule 21.01(1)(b) allows for a pleading to be struck on the ground that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or defence.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01 (1)(b).</P1></P>
<P>11. Rule 21.01 (2) stipulates that no evidence is admissible on a motion under 21.01 (1)(b).
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01 (2).</P1></P>
<P>12. The test that is applied to determine whether a pleading discloses a reasonable cause of action or defence is the &ldquo;plain and obvious test.&rdquo; The moving party must show that it is plain, obvious and beyond doubt that the respondent could not succeed in the claim or defence.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>K. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>13. The power of the Court to strike out claims that have no reasonable prospect of success is a valuable housekeeping measure that is essential to effective and fair litigation. By properly exercising the power to strike, the Court can unclutter the proceeding and weed out the hopeless claims. This ensures that only those claims that have some chance of success go on to a trial.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>K. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>14. Eliminating defences that have no reasonable cause of defence promotes efficiency in the conduct of the litigation and correct results. This allows both the litigants, the judges and juries to focus their attention where it should be&mdash;on claims that have a reasonable chance of success.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>15. A motion to strike for failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action or defence proceeds on the basis that the facts pleaded are true, unless they are manifestly incapable of being proven. Additionally, no evidence is permissible on such a motion.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>16. Whether the evidence substantiates the pleaded facts, now or at some future date, is irrelevant to the motion to strike. The judge on the motion to strike cannot consider what evidence adduces in the future might or might not show. To require the judge to do so would be to gut the motion to strike of its logic and ultimately render it useless.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Mischief and <EM>Ex Turpi Causa</EM> in the Wetzel Defendant's Pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>17. Paragraphs 4, 8, 9, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22 and 23 of the Wetzel pleadings all fail to disclose a reasonable cause of defence and should be struck.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Aviva Canada Inc.'s Statement of Claim dated April 23, 2018.</P1></P>
<P>18. Paragraphs 4, 8, 9, 17, 18, 19, 22 and 23 reference federal criminal law and the legal doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> to form a cause of defence. Specifically, the <EM>Wetzel</EM> defendant is alleging that the Plaintiff committed the criminal offence of mischief.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P>
<P>19. The criminal offence of Mischief is defined in Section 430 of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM>. Section 430 states that (1) every one commits mischief who wilfully: (a) destroys or damages property; (b) renders property dangerous, useless, inoperative or ineffective; (c) obstructs, interrupts or interferes with the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property; or (d) obstructs, interrupts or interferes with any person in the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 430 (1).</P1></P>
<P>20. Section 429 (3) of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM> considers the effect of having an interest in property that is destroyed or damaged. Specifically, the section stipulates that: (a) the fact that a person has a partial interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage; and (b) the fact that a person has total interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage with the intent to defraud.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 429 (3).</P1></P>
<P>21. The Wetzel Defendant alleges that by committing the criminal offence of mischief, the plaintiff should be barred in tort by the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>. The seminal Supreme Court of Canada decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC></CASEREF> considered the use of the doctrine in tort.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>5</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>22. The application of the <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> principle in both Canada and elsewhere has a chequered history.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>23. In <EM>Hall</EM>, Justice McLachlin, conducted a thorough examination of the cases where it was generally conceded that the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> may properly apply to tort actions. The goal of this thorough examination was to distill whether there was a unifying concern or theme that could serve to justify the application of the doctrine in tort.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>24. One situation where the doctrine was said to have a clear role is the case where to allow the plaintiff's tort claim would be to permit the plaintiff to profit from their wrong. Profit in these scenarios is meant in the narrow sense of a <BOLD><UNDER>direct</UNDER></BOLD> pecuniary reward for an act of wrongdoing (emphasis added). Compensation for something other than wrongdoing, such as for personal injury, would not amount to profit in this sense.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>25. In <EM>Hall</EM>, Justice McLachlin ultimately concluded that there is a need in the law of tort for a principle which permits judges to deny recovery to a plaintiff on the ground that to do so would undermine the integrity of the justice system. This power was viewed as a limited power. Its use is justified where allowing the plaintiff's claim would introduce inconsistency into the fabric of the law, either by permitting the plaintiff to profit from an illegal or wrongful act, or to evade a penalty prescribed by criminal law.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>26. In the Supreme Court of Canada's decision of <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Rothstein revisited and summarized <EM>Hall</EM> into six (6) principles to follow. The first (1) principle is an understanding that an application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine in the tort context invalidates otherwise valid and enforceable actions in tort. The second (2) principle attempts to recognize the grave consequences of applying the doctrine and cautions that it should only be used &ldquo;in very limited circumstances.&rdquo; The third (3) principle states that the only justification for the application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is the preservation of the integrity of the legal system. The fourth (4) principle states that the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine generally does not preclude an award of damages in tort because such awards tend to compensate the plaintiff rather than amount to profit. Finally, principles five (5) and six (6), states that the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is a defence in a tort action; as a defence, the onus is on the defendant to prove the illegal or immoral conduct that precludes the plaintiff's action.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>27. In <EM>Hall</EM>, the illegal conduct involved a drinking and driving incident that resulted in a vehicle rollover and significant head injuries. The driver had consumed 11 or 12 bottles of beer before taking the wheel. In <EM>Hall</EM> it was decided that the plaintiff need not be denied recovery as the compensation sought was for his injuries. Justice McLachlin stated that this could be reduced to the extent of the appellants contributory negligence, but cannot be wholly denied by reason of his disreputable or criminal conduct.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>28. In <EM>Zastowny</EM>, the plaintiff had been previously assaulted by an officer at a correctional centre. A psychologist later opined that the plaintiffs subsequent criminality resulted from the assaults. The plaintiff claimed for wage loss while incarcerated. His argument was that the reason he was incarcerated then for crimes committed, was due to the prior sexual assaults. The Court decided to apply the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi</EM> to bar damages for wage loss due to time spent in incarceration. Allowing these damages would introduce an inconsistency in the fabric of the law that compromised the integrity of the justice system. The Court reasoned that Zastowny was asking to be indemnified for the consequences of the commission of crimes for which he was found criminally responsible (and for which the prior sexual abuse did not provide a defence).
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>6, 8 and 30</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>The <EM>Insurance Act</EM> in the Wetzel Statement of Defence and Counterclaim</UNDER></TI>
<P>29. Paragraphs 20 and 21 of the Wetzel Statement of Defence and Counterclaim allege a violation of Section 233 (1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. Section 233 (1) covers misrepresentations or violations of conditions which renders insurance claims invalid. Specifically, Section 233 states:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>233.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Where,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>an applicant for a contract,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>gives false particulars of the described automobile to be insured to the prejudice of the insurer, or</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(ii)</N><SPARAP>knowingly misrepresents or fails to disclose in the application any fact required to be stated therein;</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the insured contravenes a term of the contract or commits a fraud; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>the insured willfully makes a false statement in respect of a claim under the contract,</PARAP></PARA>
A claim by the insured is invalid and the right of the insured to recover indemnity is forfeited.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. I. 8, Section 233 (1)</P1></P>
<P>30. Section 233 (1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> is designed to protect Insurers from fraudulent claims against them. It is an avenue available to the insurer to argue a valid denial of coverage and on its face provides no remedy to anyone else. It does not create a crime or an offence of any kind, but simply provides a remedy to insurers in certain circumstances.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Aviva Canada Inc.'s Statement of Claim dated April 23, 2018.</P1></P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 21.01 to the Wetzel Statement of Defence and Counterclaim</UNDER></TI>
<P>31. It is plain and obvious that the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi</EM> does not apply to the case at hand. No law works to prevent a party from being able to damage and repair their own property. As such, it is plain and obvious that paragraphs 4, 8, 9, 17, 18, 19, 22 and 23 do not disclose a reasonable cause of defence and therefore must be struck. There is no reasonable chance of success for the defence of mischief and the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>.</P>
<P>32. It is plain and obvious that the Defendant incorrectly relied on Section 233 (1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. The defence that the insurer effectively and knowingly committed fraud against itself has no reasonable chance of success and therefore must be struck.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Allegation of Entrapment in the Warda Defendants' Pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>33. Paragraphs 7, 14 and 20 of the Warda Defendants' Statement of Claim and Counterclaim make criminal allegations towards the Plaintiff. The paragraphs reference the known criminal law defence of entrapment.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiffs Notice of Motion&mdash;Warda Defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P>
<P>34. The Supreme Court of Canada defined the doctrine of entrapment in its decision <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Mack</SOC></CASEREF>. The court recognized entrapment when: (a) the authorities provide an opportunity to persons to commit an offence without reasonable suspicion or acting mala fides; or (b) having a reasonable suspicion or acting in the course of a bona fide inquiry, they [the authorities] go beyond providing an opportunity and induce the commission of an offence.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>K. v. Mack</SOC><CITE>[1988] 2 S.C.R. 903</CITE><PARANUM>115</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 21.01 to the Warda Defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim</UNDER></TI>
<P>35. It is plain and obvious that the Defendants inappropriately attempted to evoke the defence of entrapment in a civil context. There is no jurisprudence to support it. There is no foundation for this in law and no reasonable prospect that the defence of entrapment will succeed against the plaintiff. As such, paragraphs 7, 14 and 20 must be struck.</P></BLOCK6></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><EM>Rule 25.06 (1) and 25.06 (2)</EM></TI>
<P>36. The rules of pleading under Rule 25.06 (1) mandate that every pleading shall contain a concise statement of the material facts on which the party relies for the claim or defence, but not the evidence by which those facts are to be proved.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1999 194 r. 25.06 (1).</P1></P>
<P>37. The rules of pleading under Rule 25.06 (2) allow a party to raise any poi nt of law in a pleading. However, 25.06 (2) stipulates that conclusions of law may be pleaded only if the material facts supporting the conclusions are also pleaded.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 25.06 (2).</P1></P>
<P>38. In <CASEREF><SOC>Brazier v. T.T.C.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court decided that the pleading of a statute must be accompanied by the facts on which the application of the statute depends.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Brazier v. T.T.C.</SOC><CITE>[1946] O.W.N. 890</CITE><COURTJUR>Master</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 4.</P1></P>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Application of Rules 25.06 (1) and 25.06 (2) to the Wetzel Defendant's Pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>39. Contrary to Rule 25.06 (1), the Wetzel defendant introduces evidence in paragraph 10 of his Statement of Defence and Counterclaim. This is a violation of the rules of pleading and the paragraph must be struck.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P>
<P>40. Paragraphs 4, 17, 18, 19, 20 21 and 22 plead conclusions of law absent the material facts required to support the conclusions. As such, these paragraphs violate Rule 25.06 (2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> and must be struck.</P>
<P><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiffs Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 25.06 (2) to the Warda Defendants' Pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. Paragraphs 7, 14 and 20 of the Warda Defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim make conclusions of law absent the required material facts and violate Rule 25.06 (2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. As such, these paragraphs must be struck.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiffs Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P></BLOCK6></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI>Rule 25.11</TI>
<P>42. Pursuant to Rule 25.11 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, the Court may strike out or expunge all or part of a pleading, with or without leave to amend, on the ground that the pleading or other document: (a) may prejudice or delay the fair trial of the action; (b) is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious; or (c) is an abuse of process of the court.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 25.11.</P1></P>
<P>43. In <CASEREF><SOC>Craik v. Aetna Life Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC></CASEREF> the Court stated that the defendants were entitled to have the case against them set forth in intelligible form and free from irrelevant, prejudicial allegations.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Craik v. Aetna Life Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>[1995] O.J. No. 3286</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>44. In <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian National Railway Company v. Brant et al.</SOC></CASEREF> the Court decided that a pleading would be struck if it was designed solely for the purpose of atmosphere. In other words, if the only purpose of the pleading is to cast the opposing party in a bad light, it will be struck.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian National Railway Company v. Brant et al.</SOC><CITE>96 O.R. (3d) 734</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<BLOCK6><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 25.11 to the Wetzel Defendant's Pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>45. Paragraph 4 of the Wetzel Statement of Claim and Counterclaim prejudices the plaintiff by describing the plaintiff's actions as a &ldquo;deeply misguided guest.&rdquo; Further, paragraph 4 attempts to frame the Defendants accusations of illegality as something that has been admitted by the Plaintiff. The only possible purpose for including this in his Statement of Defence and Counterclaim is to cast the plaintiff in a bad light.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiffs Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P></BLOCK6></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff/moving party to this motion respectfully requests that paragraphs 4, 8, 9, 10, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22 and 23 of the Wetzel defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim be struck;</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff / moving party to this motion respectfully requests that paragraphs 7, 14, and 20 of the Warda defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim be struck;</P>
<P>3. Costs of the motion; and</P>
<P>4. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
