<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONDING FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANTS (PLAINTIFFS BY COUNTERCLAIM) 1843538 ONTARIO INC., FADY RONY WARDA and RONY AMANUEL WARDA TO THE PLAINTIFF'S RULE 21 MOTION</TI>
<P>Motion Returnable March 28, 2018</P>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. <UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER>:</TI>
<P>1. In the underlying proceeding, the Plaintiff (the &ldquo;Moving Party&rdquo;), an insurance company, devised and implemented investigative projects based on its suspicion of abuse within the automotive repair industry, simulated (&ldquo;staged&rdquo;) two motor vehicle accidents, conducted surreptitious video surveillance on unknowing private employees of an auto repair business (the &ldquo;Responding Parties&rdquo;), and commenced an action against the Responding Parties, alleging they committed fraudulent acts, conspiracy and trespass to property in the course of motor vehicle body repairs conducted at the site of McLaren Collision in Mississauga, Ontario.</P>
<P>2. The Moving Party seeks special damages from each of the Responding Parties for the torts specified in its Statement of Claim in the amount of $10,017.86, in addition to $100,000 in punitive damages and $200,000 for its &ldquo;investigative costs,&rdquo; all of which relate to the simulated collisions.</P>
<P>3. The Moving Party seeks an Order striking paragraphs 6, 7, 14, 15 and 20 of these Responding Parties' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. <UNDER>SUMMARY OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Parties</TI>
<P>4. The Plaintiff (Respondent), Aviva Canada Inc. (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;), is an insurance company duly incorporated and licensed by the laws of the Province of Ontario to carry on business as an automobile insurer.</P>
<P>5. The Defendant Michael Wetzel, (hereinafter known as &ldquo;Wetzel&rdquo;), at all material times, was employed as a Senior Auto Damage Appraiser by Aviva. Wetzel counterclaimed against Aviva for amounts owing based on allegations including wrongful dismissal. Wetzel was not included in Aviva's plan to conduct &ldquo;controlled collisions.&rdquo;</P>
<P>6. The Defendant, 1843538 Ontario Inc., is a duly incorporated company which carries on business, under the firm name and style of McLaren Auto Collision (hereinafter known as &ldquo;MAC&rdquo;), is an auto body shop located at 1095 Fewster Drive in Mississauga, Ontario.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Statement of Claim</TI>
<P>7. For the purpose of this motion only, the facts contained herein reflect those pleaded in the Statement of Claim, and are assumed to be true.</P>
<P>8. In its Statement of Claim issued April 22, 2018, at paragraph 8, Aviva pleads that:
<QUOTE><P>In 2017 Aviva was studying the auto collision repair industry in the Greater Toronto Area. Aviva purchased the Fusion and the Chrysler and then damaged the vehicles in a controlled setting. The vehicles were then appraised by an independent appraiser and taken to McLaren to have the damages appraised and repaired in the normal course of an insurance claim.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Motion Record, Exhibit A, Statement of Claim, para. 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. Paragraph 8 is the offending allegation within the Moving Parties' Statement of Claim, which, these Responding parties submit, renders the whole claim subject to being struck.</P>
<P>10. Rather than compile, analyze and opine on any data or statistics deriving from actual motorist claims for property damage in the course of its &ldquo;study,&rdquo; Aviva purchased vehicles itself, placed policies of insurance under the corporate entity it created, staged collisions between the vehicles, and placed fictitious claimants in the vehicles without disclosing the foregoing to the eventual automotive repair facilities the vehicles were taken. The scheme unfolded contrary to &ldquo;the normal course of an insurance claim.&rdquo;</P>
<P>11. In truth, in or about May, 2017, through to October, 2017, at Aviva's initiative, Aviva carried out two investigative &ldquo;projects&rdquo; designed to entrap and punish alleged perpetrators of fraud allegedly occurring within the auto body repair industry.</P>
<P>12. The projects, reduced to their essential features, involved the following:
<P1>a) Aviva purchased two motor vehicles with the intent to damage them;</P1>
<P1>b) Aviva would deliberately cause an accident involving the two motor vehicles (or &ldquo;stage&rdquo; an accident), damaging each motor vehicle;</P1>
<P1>c) Aviva would use the appraisal of an independent appraiser to assess the resulting damage;</P1>
<P1>d) The fictional owners of the vehicles would then report the &ldquo;accident&rdquo; to tow vehicle drivers after being driven to a roadside location;</P1>
<P1>e) The vehicles would be taken to an auto body repair shop (McLaren Collision Centre), where an appraiser employed by Aviva (the co-defendant Wetzel) himself assessed the vehicles and directed McLaren staff to conduct repairs accordingly; and</P1>
<P1>f) Upon release of the vehicles to the fictitious owners, independent forensic engineers hired by Aviva were tasked to determine and report on the validity of the repairs.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. <UNDER>STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW AND AUTHORITY</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Determination of Questions of Law under Rule 21.01</EM></TI>
<P>13. The Responding Parties submit that, despite the Moving Party's request that paragraphs 6 and 15 of the &ldquo;Warda Defendants'&rdquo; Statement of Claim be struck, no reason is provided by the Moving Party and indeed, no argument is directed at those paragraphs in either its Factum or Motion Record. These Responding Parties are therefore unable to identify the concerns raised by the Moving Party in relation to paragraphs 6 and 15.</P>
<P>14. These Responding Parties submit that where novel legal developments arise, the law must remain dynamic and flexible. Authority for this proposition is provided by The Right Honourable Madame Justice McLachlin (as she then was), who deliberated in <CASEREF><SOC>Knight v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>,:
<QUOTE><P>Actions that yesterday were deemed hopeless may tomorrow succeed. Before <CASEREF><SOC>McAlister (Donoghue) v. Stevenson</SOC><CITE>[1932]. A.C. 562</CITE><COURTJUR>U.K. H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> introduced a general duty of care to one's neighbour premised on foreseeability, few would have predicted that, absent a contractual relationship, a bottling company could be held liable for physical injury and emotional trauma resulting from a snail in a bottle of ginger beer. Before <CASEREF><SOC>Hedley Byrne &amp; Co. v. Heller &amp; Partners Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1963] 2 All E.R. 575</CITE><COURTJUR>U.K. H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, a tort action for negligent misstatement would have been regarded as incapable of success. The history of our law reveals that often new developments in the law first surface on motions to strike or similar preliminary motions, like the one at issue in <CASEREF><SOC>McAlister (Donoghue) v. Stevenson</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>Therefore, on a motion to strike, it is not determinative that the law has not yet recognized the particular claim. The court must rather ask whether, assuming the facts pleaded are true, there is a reasonable prospect that the claim will succeed. The approach must be generous and err on the side of permitting a novel but arguable claim to proceed to trial.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Knight v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 CarswellBC 1968</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. These Responding Parties submit that the inverse holds true with respect to the applicability of defences not conventionally raised in the context of civil claims, where novel claims are advanced and equally novel defences ought to be permitted.</P>
<P>16. These Responding Parties submit that the defence of entrapment is nowhere referenced at paragraph 20 of these Defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim. Instead, the allegation contained at paragraph 20 falls more squarely within the pleading of negligent investigation than any element of entrapment.</P>
<P>17. These Responding Parties further submit that, at no time do the Responding Parties plead the specific defence of &ldquo;Entrapment&rdquo; as it is conventionally used in the criminal law context. At paragraphs 7 of the Warda's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim, these Defendants use the phrase &ldquo;designs of entrapping&rdquo;, referring to the nature of the Plaintiff's planned project and its consequences. These Responding Parties remind this Honourable Court that despite the Plaintiff's plan to place controls on its scheme, it did not control for the actions of its own appraiser, who is a co-defendant in this same action. Emphasis ought to be placed on the word &ldquo;designs&rdquo; rather than the word &ldquo;entrap,&rdquo; in the sense that a conspiracy to ensnare any of a number of subjects in the Plaintiff's &ldquo;study&rdquo; occurred.</P>
<P>18. These Responding Parties further submit that in paragraph 14 of their Statement of Defence and Counterclaim, the word &ldquo;entrapment&rdquo; is used to provide context of a result that might have occurred, should the Court agree with the description of the nature of the Plaintiff's scheme as criminal activity. The true pleading at paragraph 14 is the defence of <EM>ex turpi causa non oritur actio</EM>.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>THE NOVEL NATURE OF THE PLAINTIFF'S ACTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>19. Historically, projects of the kind created by the Plaintiff have unfolded according to concerns of wrongdoing, and in concert with police activity. One example these Responding Parties can point to is Project Whiplash, which was a joint project among the Insurance Bureau of Canada, the Toronto Police Service and a number of insurance companies. Of note, the concerns of wrongdoing arose through the investigation of earlier claims submitted by third party drivers.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Jeeva</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCJ 307 (Canlii)</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. These Responding Parties respectfully submit that, should the Court ultimately allow the Plaintiff's action to proceed, these Responding Parties ought not be constrained from advancing defences normally applicable in the criminal law context, and have their actions adjudged by members of the community. The defences of entrapment, necessity and duress, by their very nature, address a range of exculpability on the part of defendants in the criminal sphere, identical to the projects designed by the Plaintiff in this civil action. The defence of entrapment ought to be permitted especially in these circumstances, in which the Plaintiff is seeking to conduct the trial by jury.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Mack</SOC><CITE>1988 CarswellBC 701</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 88&ndash;90, 122-13.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. <UNDER>ORDER REQUESTED</UNDER>:</TI>
<P>21. In light of the above, the Repsonding Parties respectfully request:
<P1>a) The Moving Party's/ Plaintiff's motion under Rule 21 be dismissed;</P1>
<P1>b) Costs of this motion; and</P1>
<P1>c) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
