<BLOCK0><TI>RESPONDING FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANT (PLAINTIFF BY COUNTERCLAIM) MICHAEL WETZEL</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY</TI>
<P>1. The plaintiff (defendant by counterclaim) Aviva Canada Inc. (&ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;) has brought forth a motion, pursuant to rules 21.01, 25.06 and 25.11 of the Rules of Civil Procedure, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, as amended (the &ldquo;Rules&rdquo;), seeking an order striking and/or dismissing various paragraphs of the Statement of Defence and Counterclaim of the defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) Michael Wetzel (&ldquo;Wetzel&rdquo;). Similar relief under the same Rules is also being sought by Aviva as against the other named defendants (the &ldquo;Warda Defendants&rdquo;). In response to this motion, both Wetzel and the Warda Defendants have brought forth their own Rule 21 motions, wherein they seek to dismiss Aviva's action in its entirety as a matter of law. In addition, Wetzel is also seeking summary dismissal of Aviva's claim pursuant to Rule 20 of the Rules; thus, for the purposes of that motion, evidence has been produced and will be relied upon. Accordingly, proceeding on March 28, 2019 before the same Judge is a triumvirate of motions, one brought by each set of parties.</P>
<P>2. The issues raised by Aviva in its moving factum, especially in regards to the law regarding (i) <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, (ii) fraud under the Ontario <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, and (iii) criminal mischief under the <EM>Criminal Code</EM> have already been extensively addressed in the Factum of the Defendant (Plaintiff by Counterclaim) Michael Wetzel, dated March 19, 2019 (&ldquo;Wetzel's Moving Factum&rdquo;). Accordingly, not only will Wetzel's Moving Factum be utilized in support of the relief that he seeks in his motion, but will also be utilized in response to Aviva's motion. Thus, the factual background and legal analysis stated therein will not be repeated again other than to state that such background and analysis are incorporated herein by reference, and will be fully relied upon at the motion hearing in response to Aviva's motion.</P>
<P>3. This responding factum, however, has been prepared specifically to address the few discrete issues raised in Aviva's factum which were not in issue in Wetzel's Moving Factum. These issues, and their analysis, now follow.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;AVIVA'S RULE 21 ARGUMENTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI><EM>Ex Turpi Causa</EM></TI>
<P>4. At para. 31 of Aviva's factum, the following was stated therein:
<QUOTE><P>31. It is plain and obvious that the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> does not apply to the case at hand. <UNDER>No law works to prevent a party from being able to damage and repair their own property</UNDER>. As such, it is plain and obvious that paragraphs 4, 8, 9, 17, 18, 19, 22 and 23 do not disclose a reasonable cause of defence and therefore must be struck. There is no reasonable chance of success for the defence of mischief and the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
(Emphasis added.)</P>
<P>5. However, there is a fundamental flaw with the foregoing analysis: On a Rule 21 motion, which is what Aviva is moving under, the facts as disclosed in Wetzel's pleadings <UNDER>must</UNDER> be assumed as true. This statement of law is well-settled, and was recently enunciated in <CASEREF><SOC>Rebello v. The Bank of Nova Scotia</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 7127</CITE></CASEREF> (per F.L. Myers, J.) as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[5] I approach the motion to determine if the fresh as amended statement of claim sets out recognized causes of action or a series of factual allegations that, if proven, would entitle the plaintiff to a legal remedy. The rules guiding this exercise are not in doubt. First, with few exceptions, <UNDER>I am required to assume that all of the facts alleged in the plaintiff's fresh as amended statement of claim are true</UNDER>. The issue is not whether the plaintiff can prove the things she alleges. Proof comes later. At this stage, the issue is just whether the plaintiff has alleged a coherent set of facts that can possibly provide her with a basis for obtaining judgment against the defendant under the applicable law. Second, I am required to read the statement of claim generously. That is, I am not trying to end the lawsuit just because lawyers can read the words used in a statement of claim in a narrow or technical sense that might not support a case. Third, I am not to dismiss the claim if it raises a very difficult or novel issue of law. If, however, assuming the facts to be true and reading the claims generously, it is plain and obvious that the plaintiffs cannot win the lawsuit, then I must dismiss the case now and save everyone the expense and trouble of dealing with it further for no reason. <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 42 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Hunt v. Carey Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>1990 CanLII 90</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE>
(Emphasis added.)</P>
<P>6. At paras. 19 of Wetzel's pleadings, the following was stated:
<QUOTE><P>19. In the case at bar, and contrary to what has been alleged by the plaintiff Aviva, <UNDER>none of the damaged cars were owned by Aviva</UNDER>. Accordingly, the admitted fact that Aviva deliberately damaged the cars in question necessarily means that it has committed the criminal offence of mischief.</P></QUOTE>
(Emphasis added.)</P>
<P>7. Accordingly, pursuant to settled law that, for the purposes of a Rule 21 motion, the impugned pleadings are &ldquo;assumed to be true&rdquo;, it necessarily follows that Aviva's argument in this regard must fail. Aviva did not damage its own property; rather, as pled, it deliberately damaged someone else's property, and thus <EM>prima facie</EM> committed criminal mischief.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><EM>Insurance Fraud</EM></TI>
<P>8. At para. 32 of Aviva's factum, the following was stated therein:
<QUOTE><P>32. It is plain and obvious that the Defendant [i.e., Wetzel] incorrectly relied on Section 233(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. <UNDER>The defence that the insurer effectively and knowingly committed fraud against itself</UNDER> has no reasonable chance of success and therefore must be struck.</P></QUOTE>
(Emphasis added.)</P>
<P>9. Once again, Aviva makes the fundamental mistake of disregarding what actually has been pled by Wetzel. In particular, para. 21 of Wetzel's pleadings stated as follows:
<QUOTE><P>21. In the case at bar, both insureds, after the &ldquo;accidents&rdquo; in question had occurred, wilfully made false statements in respect of their claims to Aviva since they knew that no &ldquo;accident&rdquo; had in fact occurred and that the whole thing was staged. Accordingly, pursuant to subsections 233(l)(b) and (c) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, each insureds contract of insurance with Aviva was rendered &ldquo;invalid&rdquo;, and their right to recover indemnity from the insurer Aviva was &ldquo;forfeited&rdquo;. Accordingly, since Aviva paid insurance under &ldquo;forfeited&rdquo; contracts, it can &ldquo;recover&rdquo; its losses by claiming back as the against the insureds themselves.</P></QUOTE>
Accordingly, as pled by Wetzel, this is <UNDER>not</UNDER> a case of fraud by Aviva as against itself; rather, this is a case of fraud committed by the insureds as against their insurer, which happened in this case to be Aviva. Thus, Aviva's second (and last) Rule 21 issue similarly fails.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;AVIVA'S RULE 25 ARGUMENTS</TI>
<P>10. Rule 25 of the Rules is simply a pleadings motion. The law in regards thereto was succinctly summarized in <CASEREF><SOC>Medad v. Steinberg</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 1480</CITE></CASEREF> (per Master P.T. Sugunasiri) as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[3] <BOLD><UNDER>Law and Analysis:</UNDER></BOLD></P>
<P>[4] The rules of pleadings are set out in Rule 25 of the Rules of Civil Procedure (&ldquo;Rules&rdquo;). Pleadings in an action can include a statement of claim, statement of defence, counterclaim and reply. Rule 25.06 applies to all pleadings. Rule 25.07 governs defences. Rule 25.08 refers to replies. Rule 25.11 gives the court discretion to strike pleadings if they are frivolous, vexatious or an abuse of process. All of these sub-rules apply to the issue to be resolved in the within motion, namely if portions of Medad's Reply and Defence to CC ought to be struck. I set out the relevant portions of the rules below:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>25.6</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><TI><EM>Material Facts</EM></TI><SSECP>Every pleading shall contain a concise statement of the material facts on which the party relies for the claim or defence, but not the evidence by which those facts are to be proved.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI><EM>Pleading Law</EM></TI><SSECP>A party may raise any point of law in a pleading, but conclusions of law may be pleaded only if the material facts supporting them are pleaded.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>25.7</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In a defence, a party shall admit every allegation of fact in the opposite party's pleading that the party does not dispute.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI>Denials in a Defence</TI><SSECP>Subject to subrule (6), all allegations of fact that are not denied in a party's defence shall be deemed to be admitted unless the party pleads having no knowledge in respect of the fact.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI><EM>Different Version of Facts</EM></TI><SSECP>Where a party intends to prove a version of the facts different from that pleaded by the opposite party, a denial of the version so pleaded is not sufficient, but the party shall plead the party's own version of the facts in the defence.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>25.8</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>A party who intends to prove a version of the facts different from that pleaded in the opposite party's defence shall deliver a reply setting out the different version, unless it has already been pleaded in the claim.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI><EM>Affirmative Reply</EM></TI><SSECP>A party who intends to reply in response to a defence on any matter that might, if not specifically pleaded, take the opposite party by surprise or raise an issue that has not been raised by a previous pleading shall deliver a reply setting out that matter, subject to subrule 25.06 (5) (inconsistent claims or new claims).</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI><EM>Reply Only Where Required</EM></TI><SSECP>A party shall not deliver a reply except where required to do so by subrule (1) or (2).</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(4)</N><TI><EM>Deemed Denial of Allegations Where No Reply</EM></TI><SSECP>A party who does not deliver a reply within the prescribed time shall be deemed to deny the allegations of fact made in the defence of the opposite party.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<SEC><N>25.11</N><TI><EM>Pleadings is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious</EM></TI><SECP>The court may strike out or expunge all or part of a pleading or other document, with or without leave to amend, on the ground that the pleading or other document,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>may prejudice or delay the fair trial of the action;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>is an abuse of the process of the court.</PARAP></PARA></SECP></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>[5] In addition to the application of these rules in determining the propriety of pleadings, a court should be mindful of the following general principles:
<P1>a. Pleadings that are irrelevant, argumentative or inserted for colour, or that constitute bare unfounded allegations should be struck out as scandalous;</P1>
<P1>b. A material fact is a fact that is necessary for a complete cause of action and a fact that can have an effect on the determination of a party's rights;</P1>
<P1>c. A pleading that raises an issue that can have no effect upon the outcome of the action is embarrassing and may be struck out;</P1>
<P1>d. A pleading should not describe the evidence that will prove a material fact. What this prohibition is designed to do is restrain the pleading of facts that are subordinate and that merely tend to prove the truth of the substantial facts in issue;</P1>
<P1>e. The distinction between material facts, particulars, and evidence is not a &ldquo;bright line&rdquo;. There will be situations where the minimum level of fact disclosure may require a pleading of material facts that might also be regarded as evidence.</P1>
<P1>f. A pleading cannot be scandalous if it is relevant;</P1>
<P1>g. A defendant is entitled to plead whatever material facts it chooses in response to the plaintiff's allegations, provided the facts alleged by the defence are relevant and at least of marginal probative value that is not outweighed by their prejudicial effect. It is not for the court the prune the case at the pleadings stage and limit allegations to what the court considers is a reasonable defence;</P1>
<P1>h. While pleadings must not offend the Rules, it is well established that counsel may frame their pleadings as they deem advisable and this right should not be lightly infringed by the court. The inclusion of unnecessary detail or excessive verbosity in a pleading is not of itself a reason for striking out a pleading. It is incumbent upon the party seeking to strike out pleadings to show that he or she is prejudiced or embarrassed by the pleading or that a fair trial will be delayed by the irregularity; and</P1>
<P1>i. If a part of a pleading is struck out because it is pleading evidence, then that would not preclude the admissibility of the evidence as proof of the plaintiff's cause of action.9 I would add that such admissibility is subject to any privileges or other evidentiary exclusions that the trier of fact applies. I would also add that striking a pleadings as evidence does not preclude an exploration of that evidence at discovery.</P1></P></QUOTE>
(Internal citations omitted.)</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Pleading Law</TI>
<P>11. At para. 40 of Aviva's factum, the following was stated:
<QUOTE><P>40. Paragraphs 4, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21 and 22 plead conclusions of law absent the material facts required to support the conclusions. As such, these paragraphs violate Rule 25.06(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> and must be struck.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. This statement, of course, is demonstrably false. The factual underpinnings of the federal statutory offence of criminal mischief, the common law doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, and violations under the Ontario <EM>Insurance Act</EM> have all been <UNDER>fully</UNDER> set out in Wetzel's pleadings. Aviva's problem, however, lies in its mistaken belief that the vehicles that were deliberately damaged were its own; as pled, they clearly were not. Accordingly, Aviva's argument here must also fail.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><EM>Pleading Evidence</EM></TI>
<P>13. At para. 39 of Aviva's factum, Aviva alleged that Wetzel &ldquo;introduces evidence in paragraph 10&rdquo; and, as a result thereof, should be struck as being contrary to rule 25.06(1) of the Rules. Aviva misunderstands the law. As stated in <EM>Medad</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, &ldquo;[t]he distinction between material facts, particulars, and evidence is not a &ldquo;bright line&rdquo;. There will be situations where the minimum level of fact disclosure may require a pleading of material facts that might also be regarded as evidence.&rdquo; At para. 10, Wetzel listed what Aviva claims were the items that it was allegedly overcharged for. This is highly relevant to Wetzel's case in that it (i) demonstrates where Wetzel's appraisal coincides with Aviva's appraisal; (ii) demonstrates where (and how) they differ; and (iii) demonstrates discrepancies between the two appraisals and the work actually done (as determined by Aviva). These are all highly relevant and material facts that directly go to the merits of the case. Accordingly, there is no violation of any pleadings rule.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI><EM>Pleadings &ldquo;Scandalous&rdquo; or &ldquo;Prejudicial&rdquo;</EM></TI>
<P>14. At para. 45 of Aviva's factum, Aviva takes issue with para. 4 of Wetzel's pleadings on account of his description of Aviva's actions as being a &ldquo;deeply misguided quest&rdquo;. Aviva continues by stating that Wetzel's &ldquo;attempts to frame the Defendants accusations of illegality as something that has been admitted by the Plaintiff&rdquo;, and that &ldquo;[t]he only possible purpose for including this in his Statement of Defence and Counterclaim is to cast the plaintiff in a bad light.&rdquo; Once again, Aviva misunderstands the law. Again as summarized in <EM>Medad</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, &ldquo;A pleading <UNDER>cannot</UNDER> be scandalous if it is relevant.&rdquo; (Emphasis added.) Though Aviva may not want to acknowledge the truth of the matter, it has readily conceded that the vehicles in question were deliberately damaged by itself. As pled by Wetzel, these vehicles were not owned by Aviva. Accordingly, Aviva has admitted to all of the constituent elements of criminal mischief. This is clearly relevant and thus not scandalous.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>15. Aviva has brought forth a pleadings motion in the hope of short-circuiting the crux of Wetzel's defence. Needless to say, this motion should be dismissed in its entirety. The fundamental flaw permeating Aviva's motion is its failure to recognize what actually has been pled by Wetzel. In particular, since Wetzel has clearly pled that the vehicles in question were <UNDER>not</UNDER> owned by Aviva, Aviva is in no position to argue against this factual statement in its Rule 21 motion. Accordingly, both issues that it raises under Rule 21, since they suffer from the same defect, must fail. With regards to its Rule 25 pleadings motion, Aviva misconstrues the law. Though Aviva may subjectively view Wetzel's pleadings as being &ldquo;scandalous&rdquo; and &ldquo;prejudicial&rdquo; as against itself, nonetheless these pleadings are clearly relevant to the issues at bar and thus clearly admissible. Accordingly, Aviva's Rule 25 pleadings motion must also fail.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>16. The defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) Michael Wetzel seeks an Order from this Court dismissing Aviva's motion in its entirety, with costs awarded in his favour on a substantial indemnity basis.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 22<SUP>nd</SUP> day of March 2019</P>
