<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) Michael Wetzel (&ldquo;Wetzel&rdquo;) brings forth this motion seeking an order, pursuant to rule 20.01(3) of the Rules of Civil Procedure, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, as amended (the &ldquo;Rules&rdquo;), dismissing, either in whole or in part, the Statement of Claim of the plaintiff (defendant by counterclaim) Aviva Canada Inc. (&ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;) as it relates specifically to himself. Additionally and/or alternatively, Wetzel seeks an order, pursuant to rules 21.01(l)(a), 21.01(l)(b) and/or 21.01(3)(d) of the Rules, striking and/or dismissing the Statement of Claim of Aviva, either in whole or in part, on the basis that it discloses no reasonable cause of action and is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court. Wetzel also seeks his costs of the motion on a substantial indemnity basis. Aviva, for its part, is not only opposing this motion, but has brought forth its own motion, pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 of the Rules, seeking to strike several paragraphs from Wetzel's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim. (In order not to unduly complicate this Factum, a separate Responding Factum will be prepared and utilized by Wetzel in response to Aviva's motion.) Finally, the other named defendants in the herein action (<EM>i.e.</EM>, collectively the &ldquo;Warda Defendants&rdquo;) have brought forth their own Rule 21 motion, wherein they seek the dismissal of Aviva's action as it relates to themselves. Accordingly, three separate motions, one for each set of parties, will be heard contemporaneously before the same Judge on the selected motions hearing date of March 28, 2019. For the reasons to be given herein, Wetzel respectfully submits that his motion seeking summary dismissal of Aviva's claim be granted.</P></BLOCK1></BLOCK0>
<BLOCK0><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;BACKGROUND</TI>
<BLOCK1><N>A.</N><TI><EM>&ldquo;Project Bumper 1A&rdquo;</EM></TI>
<P>2. Aviva, in a truly misguided attempt to identify and punish alleged fraudsters in the automobile accident repair business, embarked on a scheme which entailed damaging cars through deliberately staged (i.e., fake) car accidents, which were subsequently sent to auto body repair shops (i.e., the Warda Defendants) in order to determine the discrepancy (if any) between the true extent of the damage, as assessed and quantified by Aviva, on the one hand, and the reported damage, as assessed and invoiced by the defendants, on the other hand. <EM>See</EM> para. 6 of the Affidavit of Michael Wetzel, sworn November 2, 2018 (&ldquo;Wetzel Affidavit&rdquo;), found at Tab 2 of the Motion Record of the Defendant (Plaintiff by Counterclaim) Michael Wetzel (&ldquo;Wetzel Motion Record&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. The first of Aviva's schemes was code-named &ldquo;Project Bumper 1A&rdquo;. This scheme, and how it unfolded, was described in a confidential and internal Aviva memorandum as follows:
<QUOTE><P>This scenario utilized two Concealed Validation (CV) vehicles, a 2010 Ford Fusion SEL (CV004) and a 2012 Mazda 5GS (CV005). Both vehicles were equipped with hidden surveillance cameras capable of recording video only. Manufactured damage was created on both vehicles to simulate a collision between the two. The damage was appraised. The vehicles were then driven by individual private investigators (UC) from two different Private Investigation companies to a pre-arranged location to commence the collision scenario. The following Synopsis is in regards to CV004&mdash;the 2010 Ford Fusion.</P>
<P>On Wednesday, April 26, 2017, Aviva Canada investigators met with Discovery Group of Investigators (DGI) representatives. A scenario briefing package was supplied and a briefing took place.</P>
<P>On Monday May 8, 2017, the Aviva Canada investigators met with Wally Clark, an independent appraiser from Niagara Appraisal Services, and John Sandeman, a videographer from Video Support Services, at an arranged location. <UNDER>The Aviva Canada investigators damaged CV004 and CV005 in a mock collision</UNDER>. Mr. Clark appraised the damage. The damage and appraisal were video recorded by Mr. Sandeman.</P>
<P>The subsequent appraisal report from Mr. Clark placed the damage estimate to CV004 at $2,561.54, which included parts and labour [...]</P>
<P>On this same date, following the damage and appraisal Aviva Canada investigators met with representative from DGI at this same location. A briefing took place. Representatives from Secureye activated the In-Car Cameras. CV004 was then turned over to a UC from DGI. The UC was fitted with audio and video recording equipment.</P>
<P>CV004 was driven to a pre-staging area. A Surveillance Operator (SO) from DGI was assigned and present in a separate vehicle. After a briefing at the pre-staging area, the UC drove CV004 to the scenario location. The SO drove their vehicle to the surveillance location.</P>
<P>At approximately 12:00 PM, the UC arrived at the scenario location on Queensway West east of Mavis Road, Mississauga and parked behind CV005.</P>
<P>The scenario set out that CV004 was southbound on Mavis Road and was in the process of making a left turn onto The Queensway. CV004 failed to stay in the left lane, drifted slightly into the right lane, and struck CV005. The UC in CV004 would be at fault.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P><UNDER>A fictitious Aviva Canada claim number 33920039 was created</UNDER> and provided to the shop and an appraisal inspection was assigned to an Aviva Canada staff appraiser to inspect CV004 and prepare an estimate.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>On Tuesday May 16, 2017, prior to the completion of the repairs, Aviva Canada was invoiced by Ace Collision Centres, acting for McLaren Collision Centre in the net amount of $4,208.02. This included the appraisal of Mr. Wetzel of $4,880.82 less $1,000 deductible, and a tow invoice from MC Auto Towing for $327.70. The adjuster acknowledged receipt and requested a completion date for repairs.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>At 1:14 PM [on June 1, 2017] the UC attended at McLaren Collision Centre to return the rental car and retrieve CV004. [...] The UC paid the $1000 deductible and after completing the return documents for the rental car, he was provided the key to CV004.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>The invoice for total repair costs including the tow bill submitted by Ace Collision Centres for McLaren Collision Centre and MC Auto Towing was $4,208.02 was paid in full by Aviva Canada. A cheque was issued in the amount of $4,208.02 to Ace Collision Centres on June 15, 2017. The cheque was deposited and cleared the bank on June 22, 2017.</P>
<P>On June 2, 2017, an invoice was received from Mississauga Car Rental for $1,186.22. A cheque was issued for this amount payable to Mississauga Car Rental on June 15, 2017. The cheque was deposited and cleared the bank on June 28, 2017.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>(Emphasis added.) <EM>See</EM> para. 7 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P>
<P>4. After the Ford Fusion was retrieved by Aviva's private investigator, the car was immediately taken to a forensic engineering firm for examination, whose &ldquo;purpose [...] was to determine whether or not the following reported items of repair were completed, as per the insurance approved vehicle repair estimate, dated May 9, 2017.&rdquo; After completing their forensic examination, the firm concluded as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Based on our examination of the repaired 2010 Ford Fusion vehicle, it is our opinion that some of the observed and noted components and/or items listed herein, reported to have repaired/replaced, were not found to have been repaired/replaced. This conclusion is supported by the observed evidence on the subject vehicle at the time of our examination, as per the listed and identified items on the vehicle repair estimate.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>See</EM> para. 8 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>B.</N><TI><EM>&ldquo;Project Bumper Scenario 4B&rdquo;</EM></TI>
<P>5. The second Aviva scheme was code-named &ldquo;Project Bumper Scenario 4B&rdquo;. This scheme, and how it unfolded, was also described in great detail in an internal and confidential Aviva memorandum. As with the previously described scheme, two vehicles were involved, this time however a 2012 Mazda 5 (CV005) and a 2016 Chrysler 200 (CV007). On September 21, 2017, in the presence of Mr. Clark (Aviva's outside appraiser) and Mr. Sandeman (the videographer), &ldquo;Aviva Canada investigators damaged CV005 and CV007 in a mock collision.&rdquo; Mr. Clark thereafter appraised the damage at $3,484.36. On the same date, both vehicles were then driven by Aviva's private investigators to a pre&mdash;arranged location in Mississauga, where they parked the vehicles &ldquo;at the side of roadway in the curb lane. Both UCs exited their vehicles and began to converse purporting to have just been in a collision.&rdquo; Thereafter, CV007 (the 2016 Chrysler 200) was towed to the McLaren Collision Centre, where a &ldquo;fictitious claim number 34028257 was provided to McLaren Collision Centre&rdquo;, and Wetzel was then assigned the task of appraising CV007. Wetzel then appraised the value of the repairs, with the total dollar value of the suggested repairs at $9,872.65. After the repairs had been completed, Aviva's private investigator, purporting to be the owner of the car, retrieved the vehicle on October 24, 2017. <EM>See</EM> para. 9 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P>
<P>6. The vehicle, once retrieved from the body shop on October 24, 2017, was then transported to a &ldquo;designated facility&rdquo; for examination by the forensic engineering firm of De Berardis Associates Incorporated, with the stated purpose being &ldquo;to determine whether or not the reported items of repair were completed, as per the insurance approved vehicle repair estimate, dated September 25, 2017&rdquo;. The firm, after completing their examination of the subject vehicle, concluded as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Based on our examination of the repaired 2016 Chrysler 200 vehicle, as well as our review of the photographs that were taken during the September 27, 2017 appraisal inspection, it is our opinion that many of the observed and noted components listed herein, which were reported to have been repaired/replaced, were found to not have been repaired/replaced. This conclusion is supported by the observed evidence on the subject vehicle at the time of our examination, as per the listed and identified components contained on the vehicle repair estimate, dated September 25, 2017.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>See</EM> para. 10 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>C.</N><TI><EM>Commencement of Action, Exchange of Pleadings and Scheduling of Motions</EM></TI>
<P>7. On April 22, 2018, Aviva commenced the herein action. In this action, Aviva seeks as against Wetzel the following relief:
<QUOTE><P>(i) &ldquo;damages for fraudulent misrepresentation, breach of the duty of honest performance of a contract, unjust enrichment, and conspiracy to commit fraud, in the amount of $10,017.86&rdquo;;</P>
<P>(ii) &ldquo;damages in the amount of $100,000 for investigative costs&rdquo;;</P>
<P>(iii) &ldquo;punitive and exemplary damages in the sum of $200,000&rdquo;; and</P>
<P>(iv) pre- and post-judgment interest, and costs on a substantial indemnity basis.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>See</EM> para. 2 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P>
<P>8. In response to this action, Wetzel retained legal counsel, who thereafter prepared and served on his client's behalf a Statement of Defence and Counterclaim, dated July 16, 2018. Subsequently, the Warda Defendants retained their own legal counsel, who similarly prepared and served on his clients' behalf a Statement of Defence and Counterclaim, dated October 15, 2018. <EM>See</EM> paras. 3 and 4 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid</EM>.</P>
<P>9. Finally, at a 9:30 am in-chambers appointment before Justice Glustein on October 12, 2018, the learned Judge ordered that all three motions proceed contemporaneously for adjudication before the same Judge. (The in-chambers appointment had previously been ordered by Justice Diamond at Civil Practice Court to determine whether Aviva's pleadings motion had to be heard first or whether all motions could be heard together.) <BOLD><EM>See</EM></BOLD> para. 5 of the Wetzel Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;LAW AND ANALYSIS</TI>
<P>10. There are three issues that will be addressed in the herein motion. These issues are as follows:
<QUOTE><P>(i) Has Aviva, by admittedly engaging in the deliberate and willful destruction of property not owned by itself, which by definition qualifies as the criminal code violation of mischief, forfeited its right to sue on account of any damages that it may have sustained by virtue of the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>?;</P>
<P>(ii) Has Aviva, by admittedly paying monies under claims which it knew were fraudulent (on account of the staged accidents) and thus invalid under provincial insurance legislation, further forfeited its right to sue for damages as against any of the named defendants?; and</P>
<P>(iii) Notwithstanding any federal criminal or provincial insurance legislation, should Aviva's claim be dismissed, pursuant to the Court's inherent jurisdiction, as an abuse of the process of the Court in that Aviva has instituted an action arising solely from its own fictitious &ldquo;accidents&rdquo;. In other words, should Aviva be prevented from pursuing this action on account of having engaged in what amounts to the civil equivalent of entrapment?</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>A.</N><TI><EM>Ex Turpi Causa</EM></TI>
<P>11. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Les Laboratoires Servier v. Apotex Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2014] UKSC 55</CITE></CASEREF> (per Lord Sumption), the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>13. English law has a long-standing repugnance for claims which are founded on the claimant's own illegal or immoral acts. The law on this point was already well established when Lord Mansfield CJ articulated it in his celebrated statement of principle in <CASEREF><SOC>Holman v. Johnson</SOC><YEAR>1775</YEAR><CITE>1 Cowp. 34L, 343</CITE></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>No court will lend its aid to a man who founds his cause of action on an immoral or an illegal act. If, from the plaintiff's own stating or otherwise, the cause of action appears to arise <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, or the transgression of a positive law of this country, there the court says that he has no right to be assisted. It is upon that ground the court goes; not for the sake of the defendant, but because they will not lend their aid to such a plaintiff. So if the plaintiff and defendant were to change sides, and the defendant was to bring his action against the plaintiff, the latter would then have the advantage of it; for where both are equally in fault, potior est condition defendentis.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>Lord Mansfield's formulation begs many questions. But as these citations show, two features of this area of law have been characteristic of it from the outset. <UNDER>First, it is a rule of law and not a mere discretionary power. Secondly, it is based on public policy, and not on the perceived balance of merits between the parties to any particular dispute</UNDER>.</P>
<P>(Emphasis added.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>1993 CanLII 141</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada (per McLachlin, J. (as she then was), for the majority), ruled in relevant part (at page 170) as follows: &ldquo;The power expressed in the maxim <EM>ex turpi causa non oritur actio</EM> finds its roots in the insistence of the courts that the judicial process not be used for abusive, illegal purposes.&rdquo; At page 171, the Supreme Court further stated as follows: &ldquo;The use of the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> to prevent abuse and misuse of the judicial process is well established in contract law and insurance law, where it provokes little controversy.&rdquo; Finally, at pages 175-176, the Supreme Court stated as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The narrow principle illustrated by the foregoing examples of accepted application of the maxim of <EM>ex turpi causa non oritur actio</EM> in tort, is that a plaintiff will not be allowed to profit from his or her wrongdoing. [...] A more satisfactory explanation for these cases, I would venture, is that to allow recovery in these cases would be to allow recovery for what is illegal. It would put the courts in the position of saying that the same conduct is both legal, in the sense of being capable of rectification by the court, and illegal. It would, in short, introduce an inconsistency in the law. It is particularly important in this context that we bear in mind that the law must aspire to be a unified institution, the parts of which&mdash;contract, tort, the criminal law&mdash;must be in essential harmony. [...] We thus see that the concern, put at its most fundamental, is with the integrity of the legal system.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>13. In <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 4</CITE></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada (per Rothstein, J.), ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[20] The question is, &ldquo;under what circumstances should the immoral or criminal conduct of a plaintiff bar the plaintiff from recovering damages to which he or she would otherwise be entitled&rdquo; (p. 169). The following principles and approach are established in <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC></CASEREF> and are applicable in the present case.
<P1>1. Application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine in the tort context invalidates otherwise valid and enforceable actions in tort (p. 169).</P1>
<P1>2. Therefore, its application must be based on a firm doctrinal foundation and be made subject to clear limits and should occur &ldquo;in very limited circumstances&rdquo; (p. 169).</P1>
<P1>3. The only justification for its application is the preservation of the integrity of the legal system. This concern is only in issue where a damage award in a civil suit would allow a person to profit from illegal or wrongful conduct or would permit evasion or rebate of a penalty prescribed by the criminal law (p. 169).
<QUOTE><P>It would, in short, introduce an inconsistency in the law. It is particularly important in this context that we bear in mind that the law must aspire to be a unified institution, the parts of which&mdash;contract, tort, the criminal law&mdash;must be in essential harmony. For the courts to punish conduct with the one hand while rewarding it with the other, would be to &ldquo;create an intolerable fissure in the law's conceptually seamless web&rdquo;: Weinrib, <EM>supra</EM>, at p. 42. We thus see that the concern, put at its most fundamental, is with the integrity of the legal system, [p. 176]</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>4. The <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine generally does not preclude an award of damages in tort because such awards tend to compensate the plaintiff rather than amount to &ldquo;profit&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>Such damages accomplish nothing more than to put the plaintiff in the position he or she would have been in had the tort not occurred. ... [A plaintiff should get] only the value of, or a substitute for, the injuries he or she has suffered by the fault of another. <UNDER>He or she gets nothing for or by reason of the fact he or she was engaged in illegal conduct.</UNDER> [pp. 176-77]</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>5. The <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is a defence in a tort action. The plaintiff's illegal conduct does not give rise to a judicial discretion to negate or refuse to consider the duty of care which goes to the relationship between a plaintiff and a defendant. It is independent of that relationship. The defendant may have caused harm by acting wrongly or negligently, but the &ldquo;responsibility for this wrong is suspended only because concern for the integrity of the legal system trumps the concern that the defendant be responsible&rdquo; (pp. 181-82).</P1>
<P1>6. Treating the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine as a defence places the onus on the defendant to prove the illegal or immoral conduct that precludes the plaintiff's action. And as a defence, it allows for segregation between claims for personal injury and claims that would constitute profit from illegal or immoral conduct or the evasion of or a rebate of a penalty provided by the criminal law.</P1></P>
<P>(Emphasis added.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>14. Finally, in the recent decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Apotex Inc. v. Abbott Laboratories Limited</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 7736</CITE></CASEREF> (per Lederer, J.), the Court therein ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[37] To differ between breaches of contract, tortious acts and the criminal law, making a breach of the first and acting on the second something less than illegal, and the third as the instance where the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> would apply would serve to render the law inconsistent and raise questions about its overall integrity.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Accordingly, in contrast to the UK Supreme Court decision in <EM>Les Laboratoires</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, wherein the Court there decided to limit the scope of &ldquo;illegal or immoral acts&rdquo; to breaches involving criminal and &ldquo;quasi-criminal&rdquo; acts (such as for cases of dishonesty and corruption), no such impediment arises here in Canada, where even a breach of a patent would suffice for the purposes of the <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> defence.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>B.</N><TI><EM>Aviva's Criminal Mischief</EM></TI>
<P>15. The <EM>Criminal Code</EM>, R.S.C., 1985, c. C-46, as amended (&ldquo;<EM>Code</EM>&rdquo;) defines criminal mischief as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>430.</N>
<SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Every one commits mischief who wilfully
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>destroys or damages property;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>renders property dangerous, useless, inoperative or ineffective;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>obstructs, interrupts or interferes with the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(d)</N><PARAP>obstructs, interrupts or interferes with any person in the lawful use, enjoyment or operation of property.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI>Punishment</TI><SSECP>Every one who commits mischief that causes actual danger to life is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for life.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI>Punishment</TI><SSECP>Every one who commits mischief in relation to property that is a testamentary instrument or the value of which exceeds five thousand dollars
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding ten years; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>16. Of particular relevance to the herein proceeding is subsection 429(3) of the <EM>Code</EM>, which reads as follows:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI>Interest</TI><SSECP>Where it is an offence to destroy or to damage anything,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the fact that a person has a partial interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage; and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the fact that a person has a total interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage with intent to defraud.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>17. Aviva has of course readily conceded that it deliberately (and thus wilfully) damaged the vehicles, which damages it assessed in the thousands of dollars (<EM>i.e.</EM>, over $5,000). However, it has sought to negate this mischief on the theory that the vehicles damaged were its own. However, Aviva's own evidence clearly and unequivocally establishes that they were not.</P>
<P>18. In particular, at para. 10 of the Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan, sworn December 13, 2018 (&ldquo;Dunstan Affidavit&rdquo;), found at Tab 1 of the Responding Motion Record of the Plaintiff/Defendant by Counterclaim, Aviva Canada Inc., the deponent therein swore as follows: &ldquo;The two subject vehicles, a 2010 Ford Fusion and a 2016 Chrysler 200 were each lawfully purchased by <UNDER>2526895 Ontario Inc.</UNDER> [&ldquo;252&rdquo;]&rdquo; (emphasis added).</P>
<P>19. Despite acknowledging that the two subject vehicles were owned by 252, Aviva has sought to negate the separate corporate personality of this numbered company by essentially asking that the proverbial &ldquo;corporate veil&rdquo; be lifted, and thus ha ve it nothing more than Aviva's alter ego. Thus, Aviva's deponent swore as follows:
<QUOTE><P>On July 11, 2016, the Plaintiff incorporated the numbered company [252]. Aviva has complete control of the numbered company. The directors of the numbered company are Gregory D. Somerville (Aviva's former CEO), Colin L. Simpson (Aviva's CFO) and Sharon Sandall (a former Corporate Secretary at Aviva). As directors, these individuals act solely as agents for Aviva. Any actions of the numbered company were for the sole benefit of Aviva.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>See</EM> para. 9 of the Dunstan Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P>
<P>20. Assuming in <EM>arguendo</EM> that Aviva does indeed have &ldquo;complete contro numbered company&rdquo;, does this mean that we can ignore the separate corpora of 252 and simply treat it as being one and the same as Aviva? The answer to it is respectfully submitted, is unquestionably &ldquo;no&rdquo;.</P>
<P>21. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Yaiguaje v. Chevron Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 472</CITE></CASEREF> (per Hourigan, J.A.), the Court therein ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[65] <EM>Kosmopoulos</EM> was decided approximately thirty years ago. Not surprisingly, the law has developed. The starting point is the decision of Sharpe J., as he then was, in <EM>Transamerica</EM>. Justice Sharpe rejected the notion that the test for piercing a corporate veil is &ldquo;anything like a just and equitable standard&rdquo; (p. 433). Relying on Gower: <EM>Principles of Modern Company Law</EM>, 5th ed. (London: Sweet &amp; Maxwell, 1992), he found, at p. 433, <UNDER>that there are only three circumstances where the court will pierce a corporate veil</UNDER>:
<QUOTE><P>(1) When the court is construing a statute, contract or other document;</P>
<P>(2) When the court is satisfied that a company is a &ldquo;mere facade&rdquo; concealing the true facts; and</P>
<P>(3) When it can be established that the company is an authorized agent of its controllers or its members, corporate or human.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>[66] With respect to cases where it is alleged that a subsidiary corporation is a mere facade that protects its parent corporation, in order to ignore the corporate separateness principle, the court must be satisfied that: (i) there is complete control of the subsidiary, such that the subsidiary is the &ldquo;mere puppet&rdquo; of the parent corporation; <UNDER>and</UNDER> (ii) the subsidiary was incorporated for a fraudulent or improper purpose or used by the parent as a shell for improper activity: <EM>Transamerica</EM>, at pp. 433-34.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>[76] Not only is such an argument problematic from a policy standpoint, it comes dangerously close to the adoption of the group enterprise theory of liability. That theory holds that where several corporations operate closely as part of the same &ldquo;group&rdquo; of corporations, they are in reality a single enterprise and should, accordingly, be responsible for each other's debts. <UNDER>It has been consistently rejected by our courts</UNDER>. It has also been rejected in England.</P>
<P>(Emphasis added; internal citations omitted.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>22. Prior to analyzing the three listed circumstances identified by the Court of Appeal in <EM>Yaiguaje</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, to the facts at bar, it is important to note that it is Aviva itself who seeks to pierce the corporate veil of its own subsidiary (<EM>i.e.</EM>, 252) in the hope of avoiding criminal liability and the consequences flowing therefrom. This differs radically from the usual scenario wherein some third party creditor seeks to pierce the corporate veil of another company in the hope of attaching liability to it for the purposes of collecting on its debt or claim. The undersigned is not aware of any authority where this has been allowed to occur. In fact, the exact opposite has been found. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. National Money Mart Co.</SOC><CITE>2006 CanLII 14958</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal for Ontario (per Feldman, J.A.) ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[19] The motion judge relied on the tort claim and found that the tort arguably occurred in Ontario. She was satisfied that there was sufficient evidence of a good, arguable case that the two defendants conspired together to carry out the breach of s. 347(1) of the Code. Contrary to the submission of the appellant, there can be a conspiracy between a parent and a subsidiary corporation. The appellant submits that if Money Mart was controlled by Dollar Financial to the extent alleged in the action, then it follows that any agreement between them would be tantamount to an agreement with oneself, and one cannot conspire with oneself. Although that is an interesting analysis, the appellant's position is that the two companies are independent of each other and do not operate as one. <UNDER>Either way, where one controls the other, as two separate legal entities each remains responsible in law for its own actions, even if Dollar Financial is also responsible for some or all of the actions of its subsidiary.</UNDER></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>(Emphasis added.) Accordingly, despite its alleged complete control of 252, Aviva &ldquo;remains responsible in law for its own actions&rdquo;, including its actions in the case at bar that amounted to criminal mischief.</P>
<P>23. Turning our attention now to the three &ldquo;circumstances&rdquo; identified in <EM>Yaiguaje</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, Aviva does not of course allege that 252 was incorporated for &ldquo;a fraudulent or improper purpose&rdquo;. Accordingly, circumstance (2) cannot apply since this is a required condition. Neither does circumstance (1), since the Court is not being asked to construe any statute or document. This leave only circumstance (3), which is also inapplicable. Though Aviva has alleged that the directors of 252 act as its agents, it has not alleged that 252 itself acts as Aviva's agent (nor can it). The reason for this is obvious: According to Aviva's own evidence, 252 entered into two separate contracts of insurance with Aviva, which contracts were evidenced through the issuance of two separate automobile insurance policies. Since one cannot contract with oneself, <EM>ipso facto</EM>, 252 cannot be &ldquo;an authorized agent&rdquo; acting on behalf of Aviva and thus cannot satisfy circumstance (3). In addition, as the Court made clear in <EM>Yaiguaje</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, the &ldquo;group enterprise theory&rdquo; has been consistently rejected by courts in both Canada and in England. Accordingly, even if 252 can be said to be part of the &ldquo;Aviva group of companies&rdquo;, it retains its separate legal personality as a matter of law. <EM>See</EM> para. 13 of the Dunstan Affidavit, <EM>ibid</EM>.</P>
<P>24. Having established that Aviva did in fact engage in criminal mischief by deliberately damaging two vehicles owned by another company, which criminal act <UNDER>directly</UNDER> caused all of the damages that it is currently seeking from the herein defendants, the <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> doctrine applies with full force to bar this action. As the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, stated succinctly and forcefully: &ldquo;He or she gets nothing for or by reason of the fact he or she was engaged in illegal conduct.&rdquo;</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>C.</N><TI><EM>Aviva's Payout Under Known Fraudulent Conditions</EM></TI>
<P>25. As previously mentioned, Aviva has admitted that both vehicles, which were owned by 252 at all relevant times, were insured under &ldquo;valid and active policies of automobile insurance&rdquo;. <EM>See</EM> para. 13 of the Dunstan Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM> However, despite the admitted fact that the claims submitted in regards to both staged accidents were &ldquo;fictitious&rdquo;, Aviva nonetheless still chose to pay under those policies, even though those policies were void as a matter of law. This fact was made abundantly clear in the following passages from the Dunstan Affidavit:
<QUOTE><P>12. The Plaintiff had no intent to defraud the Defendants. In fact, the plaintiff paid the Warda Defendants' invoices, notwithstanding what it believes to be fraudulent charges. In this action Aviva seeks to recover, among other things, the payments made for the fraudulent charges.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>14. The Plaintiff had full knowledge of the claims and was not committing fraud against itself.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>See</EM> paras 12 and 14 of the Dunstan Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM></P1></P>
<P>26. The relevant provisions of the Ontario <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. I.8, as amended (&ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;) read as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>233</N><TI>Misrepresentation or violation of conditions renders claim invalid</TI>
<SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Where,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>an applicant for a contract,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>gives false particulars of the described automobile to be insured to the prejudice of the insurer, or</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(ii)</N><SPARAP>knowingly misrepresents or fails to disclose in the application any fact required to be stated therein;</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the insured contravenes a term of the contract or commits a fraud; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>the insured wilfully makes a false statement in respect of a claim under the contract,</PARAP></PARA>
a claim by the insured is invalid and the right of the insured to recover indemnity is forfeited.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>27. In the case at bar, there is no question that the insured (<EM>i.e.</EM>, 252) &ldquo;wilfully [made] a false statement in respect of a claim under the contract&rdquo; by knowingly submitting the two claims on account of the staged (fake) accidents. Accordingly, pursuant to subsection 233(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>, the &ldquo;claim by the insured [was] invalid and the right of the insured to recover indemnity [was] forfeited&rdquo;. Accordingly, it is manifestly illogical (and unlawful) for Aviva to now seek damages from the defendants on account of claims that (i) it knew were fraudulent, (ii) it knew were void as a matter of law; and yet (iii) it still decided to pay them out.</P>
<P>28. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Southcott v. Toronto Catholic School Board</SOC><CITE>2012 SCC 51</CITE></CASEREF> (per Karakatsanis, J., for the majority), the Supreme Court of Canada ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>IV.</N><TI>Mitigation&mdash;General Principles</TI>
<P>[23] This Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Asamera Oil Corp. v. Seal Oil &amp; General Corp.</SOC><CITE>[1979] 1 S.C.R. 633</CITE></CASEREF>, cited (at pp. 660-61) with approval the statement of Viscount Haldane L.C. in <CASEREF><SOC>British Westinghouse Electric and Manufacturing Co. v. Underground ElectricRailways Company of London, Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1912] A.C. 673</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 689</PAGENUM></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>The fundamental basis is thus compensation for pecuniary loss naturally flowing from the breach; but this first principle is qualified by a second, <UNDER>which imposes on a plaintiff the duty of taking all reasonable steps to mitigate the loss consequent on the breach, and debars him from claiming any part of the damage which is due to his neglect to take such steps.</UNDER></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>[24] In <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Canadian Forest Products Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 38</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2004] 2 S.C.R. 74</CITE><PARANUM>176</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, this Court explained that &ldquo;[l]osses that could reasonably have been avoided are, in effect, caused by the plaintiff's inaction, rather than the defendant's wrong.&rdquo; As a general rule, a plaintiff will not be able to recover for those losses which he could have avoided by taking reasonable steps. Where it is alleged that the plaintiff has failed to mitigate, the burden of proof is on the defendant, who needs to prove both that the plaintiff has failed to make reasonable efforts to mitigate and that mitigation was possible (<CASEREF><SOC>Red Deer College v. Michaels</SOC><CITE>[1976] 2 S.C.R. 324</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Asamera; Evans v. Teamsters Local Union No. 31</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 20</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 661</CITE><PARANUM>30</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. (Emphasis added.) Accordingly, pursuant to the Supreme Court of Canada's statement in <EM>Southcott</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, that losses that &ldquo;could reasonably have been avoided are, in effect, caused by the plaintiff's inaction&rdquo;, Aviva has forfeited its right to claim any damages as aga inst any of the defendants in the herein action. <UNDER>All</UNDER> of Aviva's &ldquo;losses&rdquo; could and would have been avoided but for its decision to execute on its scheme of staging fake car accidents. In addition, since Aviva knew that the contracts of insurance were rende red void on account of the fraudulent claims submitted, yet still chose to pay out under these policies, it is now debarred from pursuing any of those losses.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>D.</N><TI><EM>Aviva's Abuse of the Process of the Court</EM></TI>
<P>29. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Toronto (City) v. C.U.P.E.. Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE></CASEREF> (per Arbour, J., for the majority), the Supreme Court ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>(3)</N><TI>Abuse of Process</TI>
<P>Judges have an inherent and residual discretion to prevent an abuse of the court's process. This concept of abuse of process was described at common law as proceedings &ldquo;unfair to the point that they are contrary to the interest of justice&rdquo; (<CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Power</SOC><CITE>[1994] 1 S.C.R. 601</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 616</PAGENUM></CASEREF>), and as &ldquo;oppressive treatment&rdquo; (<CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Conway</SOC><CITE>[1989] 1 S.C.R. 1659</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 1667</PAGENUM></CASEREF>). McLachlin J. (as she then was) expressed it this way in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Scott</SOC><CITE>[1990] 3 S.C.R. 979</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 1007</PAGENUM></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>. . . abuse of process may be established where: (1) the proceedings are oppressive or vexatious; and, (2) violate the fundamental principles of justice underlying the community's sense of fair play and decency. The concepts of oppressiveness and vexatiousness underline the interest of the accused in a fair trial. But the doctrine evokes as well the public interest in a fair and just trial process and the proper administration of justice.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>In the context that interests us here, the doctrine of abuse of process engages &ldquo;the inherent power of the court to prevent the misuse of its procedure, in a way that would ... bring the administration of justice into disrepute&rdquo; (<CASEREF><SOC>Canam Enterprises Inc. v. Coles</SOC><YEAR>2000</YEAR><CITE>51 O.R. (3d) 481</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 55, per Goudge J.A., dissenting (approved <CASEREF><CITE>[2002] 3 S.C.R. 307</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2002 SCC 63</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>)). Goudge J.A. expanded on that concept in the following terms at paras. 55-56:
<QUOTE><P>The doctrine of abuse of process engages the inherent power of the court to prevent the misuse of its procedure, in a way that would be manifestly unfair to a party to the litigation before it or would in some other way bring the administration of justice into disrepute. It <UNDER>is a flexible doctrine unencumbered by the specific requirements of concepts such as issue estoppel</UNDER>. See <CASEREF><SOC>House of Spring Gardens Ltd. v. Waite</SOC><CITE>[1990] 3 W.L.R. 347</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 358</PAGENUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[1990] 2 All E.R. 990</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>(Emphasis in original.)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>30. In the case at bar, there are many &ldquo;oppressive&rdquo; aspects of this case which militate strongly in favour of dismissal as against Aviva's claim. First, Aviva is seeking as against all defendants $100,000 for its &ldquo;investigative costs&rdquo;. This is highly problematic not only because its actual &ldquo;damages&rdquo; (<EM>i.e.</EM>, what it claims was over-billed) were only approximately $10,000, but it also literally creates the specter of <UNDER>unlimited</UNDER> liability for these defendants (and any others similarly situated) since a company like Aviva can literally spend hundreds of thousands (or even millions) of dollars on its &ldquo;investigative costs&rdquo;, had it so chosen, and thus financially ruin the defendants. This cannot be allowed to happen. Second, the action is &ldquo;oppressive&rdquo; in that, as already mentioned numerous times herein, the accidents were all staged by Aviva and thus created by it. In other words, this is not a case of a real-world accident, which was subsequently investigated by Aviva to determine whether billed work was actually performed as indicated. Finally, this case is &ldquo;oppressive&rdquo; in that it amounts to the civil equivalent of entrapment. In particular, in the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imoro</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 122</CITE></CASEREF> (per Laskin, J.A.), the Court of Appeal ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[10] Lamer J. struck the balance between these objectives by concluding that entrapment arises in either of two situations: first, when state authorities, acting without reasonable suspicion or for an improper purpose, provide a person with an opportunity to commit an offence; and second, even having reasonable suspicion or acting in the course of a good faith inquiry, the police go beyond providing an opportunity to commit a crime and actually induce the commission of an offence.</P>
<P>[11] Ordinarily, when entrapment is claimed, the essential elements of the offence charged have been made out. However, if entrapment is subsequently found, the court will not allow the Crown to maintain a conviction because to do so would be an abuse of process and bring the administration of justice in disrepute. So instead, the court will stay the proceedings.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>31. In the case at bar, Aviva has conceded that the damaged vehicles were &ldquo;randomly towed to the Warda Defendants body shop in the normal course of an insurance claim.&rdquo; <EM>See</EM> para. 11 of the Dunstan Affidavit, <EM>ibid.</EM> Accordingly, Aviva acted as against both Wetzel and the Warda Defendants &ldquo;without reasonable suspicion&rdquo;. In addition, and with the proviso of course that no wrongdoing whatsoever is conceded by any of the defendants, Aviva provided the opportunity to commit the claimed offence. In other words, if it wasn't for Aviva's staged accidents, no opportunity for any wrongdoing in the case at bar would have arisen.</P>
<P>32. <EM>En passant</EM>, it is also important to note that Aviva's claim itself may be viewed as being &ldquo;fraudulent&rdquo; and thus, by its nature, an abuse of the process of the Court. In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Cannon v. Funds for Canada Foundation</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 399</CITE></CASEREF> (per G.R. Strathy, J., as he then was), the Court therein ruled in relevant part as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[187] <UNDER>Fraud is the deprivation of another's property by dishonest means</UNDER>. While many of the classic definitions of fraud have a component of false representation (see <CASEREF><SOC>Parna v. G. &amp; S. Properties Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, above, at S.C.R. 316) or deceit (see <CASEREF><SOC>Re London and Globe Finance Corp.</SOC><CITE>[1903] 1 Ch. 728</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1900-3] All E.R. Rep. 891</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>88 L.T. 194</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>10 Mans. 198</CITE><PAGENUM>at 732-33</PAGENUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [cited to Ch.]), other cases have held that these definitions are not exhaustive and fraud can simply mean the dishonest deprivation of someone else's property. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Scott v. Commissioner of Police for the Metropolis</SOC><CITE>[1974] 3 All E.R. 1032</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1975] A.C. 819</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>60 Cr. App. Rep. 124</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>181 Sol. Jo. 863</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [cited to All E.R.], Viscount Dilhorne held at p. 1038:
<QUOTE><P>The definition of &ldquo;defraud&rdquo; in the <EM>London and Globe Finance</EM> case is not exhaustive and the word ordinarily means: &ldquo;... to deprive a person dishonestly of something which is his or of something to which he is or would or might but for the perpetration of the fraud, be entitled.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>[188] This is consistent with the definition of the criminal offence of fraud set out in s. 380 of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. C-46:
<QUOTE><P>Every one who, by deceit, falsehood or other fraudulent means, whether or not it is a false pretence within the meaning of this Act, defrauds the public or any person, whether ascertained or not, of any property, money or valuable security ...[is guilty of an offence]. [emphasis added].</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>33. Accordingly, by instituting this action, Aviva is trying to deprive Wetzel and the Warda Defendants of their property (<EM>i.e.</EM>, money) through &ldquo;dishonest means&rdquo;, as evidenced by the staged car accidents and the fictitious insurance claims.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>34. Aviva, in a truly over-zealous and misguided effort to curb what it believed to be fraudulent practices in the automobile accident body-shop repair business and the appraisers who appraise such accidents, embarked on an entirely unlawful scheme which entailed the deliberate staging of car accidents and the subsequent filing of fictitious insurance claims arising therefrom. The scheme was unlawful and criminal in that it involved the offence of criminal mischief over $5,000. The vehicles, as evidenced by Aviva itself, were owned by another company. Aviva cannot as a matter of law pierce the proverbial &ldquo;corporate veil&rdquo; and claim that this numbered company does not exist or that it is its mere alter ego. Having thus committed a criminal act, the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> acts to debar Aviva's claim in its entirety. In addition, Aviva cannot recover for &ldquo;losses&rdquo; that it itself caused. It knew that the submitted claims were fraudulent, which thus voided the contracts of insurance between 252, as the insured, and Aviva, as the insurer. Finally, Aviva's action is an abuse of the process of the Court in that, <EM>inter alia</EM>, it amounts to the civil equivalent of entrapment.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>35. The defendant (plaintiff by counterclaim) Michael Wetzel seeks an Order from this Court for the following relief:
<QUOTE><P>(i) an Order for the summary dismissal, either in whole or in part, of the plaintiff's claim pursuant to Rule 20 of the Rules;</P>
<P>(ii) Additionally and/or alternatively, an Order dismissing and/or striking, either in whole or in part, the plaintiff's claim pursuant to Rule 21 of the Rules; and</P>
<P>(iii) Costs in his favour as against the plaintiff on a substantial indemnity basis.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS</BOLD> 19<SUP>th</SUP> day of March 2019</P>
<P>&ellip35; Terry Corsianos</P>
<P>Lawyer for Michael Wetzel</P></BLOCK1></BLOCK0>
