<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P><P1>1. A total of three motions are being brought concurrently. All of the parties involved in this action have brought motions. The defendant Michael Wetzel (&ldquo;Wetzel&rdquo;) is seeking the following relief:
<P2>a) An Order, pursuant to Rule 20.01(3) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, dismissing, either in whole or in part, the Statement of Claim of the plaintiff Aviva Canada Inc. as it relates specifically to Wetzel;</P2>
<P2>b) Additionally and/or alternatively, Wetzel seeks an order pursuant to rules 21.1(1)(a), 21.01(1)(b) and/or 21.01(3)(d) of the <EM>Rules</EM>, striking and/or dismissing the Statement of Claim of Aviva, either in whole or in part, on the basis that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court; and</P2>
<P2>c) Costs on a substantial indemnity basis.</P2></P1>
<P1>2. The plaintiff and 1843538 Ontario Inc. c.o.b. Mississauga Collision Centre, and/or McLaren Collision, Fady Warda and Rony Amanuel Warda (Collectively, &ldquo;the Warda Defendants&rdquo;) will also be arguing motions on the return date of March 28, 2019. All three motions were scheduled to be heard on the same date as per the Order of Justice Glustein dated October 12, 2018.</P1>
<P1>3. The plaintiff is bringing a motion pursuant to Rules 21.01, 25.06 and 25.11 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to strike paragraphs from both the Warda defendants' and Wetzel's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>4. The Warda defendants are moving under Rule 21.01(1)(a) and 21.01(1)(b) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P><P1>5. By Statement of Claim issued on April 23, 2018, the plaintiff commenced an action to recover damages for fraudulent misrepresentation, breach of duty of honest performance of a contract, unjust enrichment, and conspiracy to commit fraud. Additionally, the plaintiff sought to recover damages for trespass to property, investigative costs and punitive and exemplary damages.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 3.</P1>
<P1>6. Wetzel delivered his Statement of Defence and Counterclaim on July 16, 2018.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 4.</P1>
<P1>7. The Warda defendants delivered their Statement of Defence and Counterclaim on October 15, 2018.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 5.</P1>
<P1>8. The moving party was at all material times employed as a Senior Auto Damage Appraiser by the plaintiff. The plaintiff, Aviva, determined that Wetzel, during the course of his employment, knowingly engaged in serious breaches of conduct. This included but is not limited to a breach of Aviva Canada's Code of Conduct.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at paras 6 and 8.</P1>
<P1>9. The plaintiff incorporated its numbered company 2526895 Ontario Inc. (&ldquo;252&rdquo;) on July 11, 2016. Aviva is the only shareholder of the numbered company and has complete control of it. Any actions of said numbered company were for the sole benefit of Aviva. The two subject vehicles involved in the plaintiffs investigation were lawfully purchased by 252.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at paras 9 and 10.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Supplementary Motion Record at Tab 8.</P1>
<P1>10. As part of its investigation, the plaintiff damaged these vehicles in a safe and controlled setting. Following the damage, the vehicles were randomly towed to the Warda defendants' body shop in the normal course of an insurance claim.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 11.</P1>
<P1>11. Prior to the vehicles being towed to the Warda defendants' body shop, the plaintiff had its own independent appraisals conducted. These were done prior to the appraisal and repairs being completed by the defendants. The moving defendant in this motion, Wetzel, completed routine appraisals in the regular course of business on each of the subject vehicles at the Warda defendants' body shop.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at paras 15 and 16.</P1>
<P1>12. After the subject vehicles were returned by the Warda defendants to the plaintiff, further independent appraisals were done to inspect the work that was completed. The completed work was compared against the appraisals and invoices submitted to the plaintiff and the prior appraisals conducted by the plaintiff. It was discovered that Wetzel included parts on the appraisal as being required to be replaced which in fact were not damaged and did not need to be replaced. Additionally, various parts were included on his appraisals as requiring refinishing when in fact they were not damaged and did not require refinishing. Finally, various parts were listed on the appraisal to be replaced and/or refinished which had not initially been damaged prior to the vehicle being taken to the Warda defendants, but were deliberately damaged by the Warda defendants, as revealed by discreet video recorded from the vehicle while it was in the shop of the Warda defendants.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 22.</P1>
<P1>13. As part of its Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; productions in its draft Affidavit of Documents, the plaintiff provided the defendants with a detailed synopsis of the events that gave rise to its claim.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Supplementary Motion Record&mdash;Tab 9 Supplementary Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 3.</P1>
<P1>14. In addition to a detailed synopsis of each claim, the plaintiff included appendices outlining the issues and unjustified invoicing identified along with a separate set of appendices outlining the supporting evidence in its Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; documents.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Supplementary Motion Record&mdash;Tab 9 Supplementary Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at para 4.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES</TI>
<P><P1>15. <BOLD>Whether the Court should grant summary judgement and dismiss all or part of the claim in the Statement of Claim as against Wetzel pursuant to Rule 20.01(3).</BOLD> The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that there is a genuine issue requiring a trial and its claim should not be dismissed.</P1>
<P1>16. <BOLD>Whether the Court should strike and /or dismiss of all or part of the Statement of Claim as against Wetzel pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(a).</BOLD> The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that it would be inappropriate to strike all or part of the action on these grounds.</P1>
<P1>17. <BOLD>Whether the Court should strike and/or dismiss all or part of the Statement of Claim as against Wetzel pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(b).</BOLD> The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that it has disclosed a reasonable cause of action. As such, it would be inappropriate to strike and/or dismiss the Statement of Claim on these grounds.</P1>
<P1>18. <BOLD>Whether the Court should strike and/or dismiss all or part of the Statement of Claim as against Wetzel pursuant to Rule 21.01(3)(d).</BOLD> The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that the action is not an abuse of the process of the Court. As such, it would be inappropriate to strike and/or dismiss the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim on these grounds.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;STATEMENT OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule 20</EM></TI>
<P><P1>19. Summary judgment motions serve to prevent &ldquo;claims or defences that have no chance of success from proceeding to trial...as trying unmeritorious claims imposes a heavy price in terms of time and cost on the parties to the litigation and on the justice system&rdquo;; however, the summary judgment rules have evolved to provide a legitimate alternative means for adjudicating and resolving disputes.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Attorney General) v. Lameman</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 14</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 372</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>Tab 2 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>20. The <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provide that a Court shall grant summary judgment if the Court is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to a claim or defence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 20.04(2)(a).</P1>
<P1>21. In determining whether there is a genuine issue requiring a trial, Rule 20.04(2.1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> establishes that:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he Court shall consider the evidence submitted by the parties and, if the determination is being made by a judge, the judge may exercise any of the following powers for the purpose, unless it is in the interest of justice for such powers to be exercises only at a trial:
<P1>1. Weighing the evidence.</P1>
<P1>2. Evaluation the creditability of a deponent.</P1>
<P1>3. Drawing any reasonable inference from the evidence.</P1></P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 20.04(2.1)</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>22. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, the leading case on summary judgment, the Supreme Court of Canada held that:
<QUOTE><P>There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial when the judge is able to reach a fair and just determination on the merits on a Motion for summary judgment. This will be the case when the process (1) allows the judge to make the necessary findings of fact, (2) allows the judge to apply the law to the facts, and (3) is a proportionate, more expeditious and less expensive means to achieve a just result.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> Tab 1 of the plaintiffs Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>23. In <EM>Hryniak</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada outlined the approach a Court should apply to summary judgment Motions: first, it must first determine whether there is a genuine issue for trial based only on the evidence provided, without the use of the new fact finding powers. Second, if it appears that there is a genuine issue for trial then the Court is to determine whether a trial can be avoided by exercising the powers in <EM>Rule</EM> 20.04(2.1) and (2.2). As explained by Justice Karakatsanis:
<QUOTE><P>If there appears to be a genuine issue requiring a trial, [a judge] should then determine if the need for a trial can be avoided by using the new powers under Rules 20.04(2.1) and (2.2), [a judge] may at her discretion, use those powers, provided that their use is not against the interest of justice. Their use will not be against the interest of justice if they will lead to a fair and just result and will serve the goals of timeliness, affordability and proportionality in light of the ligation as a whole.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>66</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>24. The standard for fairness is not whether the procedure is as exhaustive as a trial, but whether it gives the judge confidence that he or she can find the necessary facts and apply the relevant legal principles to resolve the dispute. Any concerns about credibility or clarification of the evidence can often be addressed by calling oral evidence on the Motion itself.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>50 and 51</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>25. While the rule for summary judgment Motions has been modified and its intended interpretation has been clarified, the guiding principles remain the same and parties to the Motion are still required to put their &lsquo;best foot forward&rsquo;. As expressed by Justice M.L. Edwards in <CASEREF><SOC>Theiventhirampillai v. City of Toronto</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>In responding to a Motion for summary judgment, a party...is required to put forward all evidence on which he intends to rely at the hearing of the Motion and cannot in response to the Motion, simply suggest that there may be other evidence available which might assist in establishing a claim.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Theiventhirampillai v. City of Toronto</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 215</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>Tab 3 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule21.01(1)(a)</EM></TI>
<P><P1>26. A complete analysis of Rule 21.01(1)(a) is also found in the plaintiffs responding factum to the Warda defendants' motion. This analysis occurs at paragraphs eleven (11) thru fifteen (15). For ease of reference, the law will be repeated below.</P1>
<P1>27. Rule 21.01(1)(a) allows for a party to move before a judge for the determination, before trial, of a question of law raised by a pleading in an action where the determination of the question may dispose of all or part of the action, substantially shorten the trial or result in a substantial saving of costs.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 21.01(1)(a).</P1>
<P1>28. The Court in <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Ontario Hydro</SOC></CASEREF> decided that the &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; test is the relevant test for both subrules (a) and (b) of rule 21.01(1).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Ontario Hydro</SOC><CITE>19 O.R. (3d) 529</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 4 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>29. In addition to the plain and obvious test, the Court has previously considered when it would be appropriate to bring a motion to dispose of a point of law. In <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. Canadian Broadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Lieff, commented on what was then Rule 124, which allowed for a point of law to be set down for a hearing at any time before the trial. Justice Lieff decided that the defendant's proper procedure is to bring a motion for a judgment on the pleadings after the pleadings are complete. This principle was later adopted by the Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. CanadianBroadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC><YEAR>1975</YEAR><CITE>8 O.R. (2d) 55</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 5 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 1274</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 6 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>30. According to Rule 25.05 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, pleadings in an action are closed when, (a) the plaintiff has delivered a reply to every defence in the action or the time for delivery of a reply has expired.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 25.05(a).</P1>
<P1>31. In <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF>, D.M. Brown J., conducted an analysis of the relevant case law related to Rule 21.01(1)(a) motions. The following general principles were extracted from the case law:
<P2>i. the rule is not designed to answer questions of law where material facts are in dispute or, put another way, where no agreement exists on the material facts which underpin the question of law posed;</P2>
<P2>ii. a party should not use Rule 21 to secure the advice of the court about the soundness of its cause of action or defence by asking the court to assume that the material facts it has pleaded will be proved at trial, thereby asking the court to answer a hypothetical question. However, the hypothetical to be avoided is one where an underpinning of the legal determination sought under Rule 21 might be altered at trial, and the legal determination thus rendered redundant;</P2>
<P2>iii. a defendant should not move for the determination of a question of law involving the applicability of a limitation period...;</P2>
<P2>iv. where the question of law depends on the construction of a contract, the terms of which are unclear and capable of more than one meaning, Rule 21 is not an appropriate device to use to anshwer the question; and</P2>
<P2>v. matters of law which have not been settled fully in the jurisprudence usually should not be disposed of at an interlocutory stage of the proceedings.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 6107</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P2>
<P2>Tab 7 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule 21.01(1)(b)</EM></TI>
<P><P1>32. As was the case with Rule 21.01(1)(a), the plaintiff provided the Court with a full analysis of Rule 21.01(1)(b) in its responding factum to the Warda defendants' motion. This analysis is found at paragraphs twenty-five (25) thru thirty (30). For ease of reference, the law will be repeated below.</P1>
<P1>33. Rule 21.01(1)(b) allows for a pleading to be struck on the ground that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or defence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01(1)(b).</P1>
<P1>34. Rule 21.01(2) stipulates that no evidence is admissible on a motion under 21.01(1)(b).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01 (2).</P1>
<P1>35. The test that is applied to determine whether a pleading discloses a reasonable cause of action or defence is the &ldquo;plain and obvious test.&rdquo; The moving party must show that it is plain, obvious and beyond doubt that the respondent could not succeed in the claim or defence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>36. The power of the Court to strike out claims that have no reasonable prospect of success is a valuable housekeeping measure that is essential to effective and fair litigation. By properly exercising the power to strike, the Court can unclutter the proceeding and weed out the hopeless claims. This ensures that only those claims that have some chance of success go on to a trial.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>37. A motion to strike for failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action or defence proceeds on the basis that the facts pleaded are true, unless they are manifestly incapable of being proven. Additionally, no evidence is permissible on such a motion.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>38. Whether the evidence substantiates the pleaded facts, now or at some future date, is irrelevant to the motion to strike. The judge on the motion to strike cannot consider what evidence adduced in the future might or might not show. To require the judge to do so would be to gut the motion to strike of its logic and ultimately render it useless.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule 21.01(3)(d)</EM></TI>
<P><P1>39. Rule 21.01(3) allows a defendant to move before a judge to have an action stayed or dismissed on the ground that, (d) the action is frivolous, vexatious or is otherwise an abuse of the process of the court, and the judge may make an order or grant judgement accordingly.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01(3)(d).</P1>
<P1>40. In <CASEREF><SOC>Diamond v. 996087 Ontario Ltd. (c.o.b. Academy for Gifted Children&mdash;P.A.C.E.)</SOC></CASEREF>, G.P. DiTomaso summarized the test under Rule 21.01(3)(d) as follows:
<QUOTE><P>...dismissing or staying an action as frivolous or vexatious or abusive of the Court's process must be reserved for the clearest of cases where on the face of the action and circumstances it is plain and obvious that the case cannot succeed.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>As such, the high bar established by the plain and obvious test also applies to Rule 21.1(3)(d).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Diamond v. 996087 Ontario Ltd. (c.o.b. Academy for Gifted Children&mdash;P.A.C.E.)</SOC><CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 4012</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 9 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>41. In <CASEREF><SOC>Temilini v. Ontario Provincal Police (Commisioner)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal was asked to review the lower Court's decision on whether or not the action was frivolous, vexatious or was otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court. Grange J.A. decided that it is sufficient to say that &ldquo;a plaintiff who asserts a proper cause of action where there is some evidence upon which the case can be built should not be foreclosed.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Temilini v. Ontario Provincial Police (Commissioner) (C.A.)</SOC><CITE>73 O.R. (2d) 664</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 10 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Application of the Statement of Law to the Issues Presented by the Wetzel's Factum as the Moving Party</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>42. Wetzel, as the moving party, is relying on Rules 20, 21.01(1)(a), 21.01(1)(b) and 21.01(3)(d) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. Part III of his factum fails to distinguish the Rules as applied to the moving party's individual arguments. In an attempt to accurately respond to the arguments presented, the plaintiff and responding party will address the arguments in the order that they appear. The plaintiff and responding party must assume that the arguments are being made under each rule, since the material does not distinguish same.</P1>
<P1>43. At Paragraph 10 of his Factum, Wetzel identifies three central issues to be addressed in the herein motion. The issues are:
<P2>i. Has Aviva, by admittedly engaging in the deliberate and willful destruction of property not owned by itself, which by definition qualifies as the criminal code violation of mischief, forfeited its right to sue on account of any damages that it may have sustained by virtue of the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>?;</P2>
<P2>ii. Has Aviva, by admittedly paying monies under claims which it knew were fraudulent (on account of the staged accidents) and thus invalid under provincial insurance legislation, further forfeited its right to sue for damages as against any of the named defendants'; and</P2>
<P2>iii. Notwithstanding any federal criminal or provincial insurance legislation, should Aviva's claim be dismissed, pursuant to the Court's inherent jurisdiction as an abuse of the process of the Court in that Aviva has instituted an action arising solely from its own fictitious &ldquo;accidents.&rdquo; In other words, should Aviva be prevented from pursuing this action on account of having engaged in what amounts to the civil equivalent of entrapment.</P2></P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>A.</EM></N><TI><EM>Ex Turpi Causa</EM></TI>
<P><P1>44. The moving party's factum then dives into an analysis of the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> under heading &ldquo;A.&rdquo; Wetzel begins his analysis of the doctrine by citing the United Kingdom decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Les Laboratoires Servier v. Apotex Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>. The responding party respectfully submits that very little weight, if any, should be attributed to the decision. It is a 2014 decision that cites an ancient English case decided in the year 1775. Canadian Courts have had the opportunity to address the doctrine and the Canadian jurisprudence on the issue has steadily evolved since the leading Supreme Court of Canada decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Les Laboratoires Servier v. Apotex Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2014] UKSC 55</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 11 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>1993 CanLII 141</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 12 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>45. The plaintiff and responding party to this motion agrees with paragraph thirteen (13) of the moving party's (Wetzel's) factum, which outlines the six principles of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> that were established by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 13 of the plaintiffs Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>46. In the case at hand, the Court must strongly consider the first two principles of applying the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> as established by <EM>Zastowny</EM>. Those principles are: (1) application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine in the tort context invalidates otherwise valid and enforceable actions in tort; and (2) therefore, its application must be based on a firm doctrinal foundation and be made subject to clear limits and should occur in very limited circumstances.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastonmy</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 13 of the plaintiffs Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>47. In <EM>Hall</EM>, the illegal conduct involved a drinking and driving incident that resulted in a vehicle rollover and significant head injuries. The driver had consumed 11 or 12 bottles of beer before taking the wheel. In <EM>Hall</EM> it was decided that the plaintiff need not be denied recovery as the compensation sought was for his injuries. Justice McLachlin stated that this could be reduced to the extent of the appellants contributory negligence, but cannot be wholly denied by reason of his disreputable or criminal conduct.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Hebert</SOC><CITE>[1993] S.C.J. No. 51</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 12 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>48. In <EM>Zastowny</EM>, the plaintiff had been previously assaulted by an officer at a correctional centre. A psychologist later opined that the plaintiff's subsequent criminality resulted from the assaults. The plaintiff claimed for wage loss while incarcerated. His argument was that the reason he was incarcerated then for crimes committed, was due to the prior sexual assaults. The Court decided to apply the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi</EM> to bar damages for wage loss due to time spent in incarceration. Allowing these damages would introduce an inconsistency in the fabric of the law that compromised the integrity of the justice system. The Court reasoned that Zastowny was asking to be indemnified for the consequences of the commission of crimes for which he was found criminally responsible (and for which the prior sexual abuse did not provide a defence).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>6, 8 and 30</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 13 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>49. The plaintiff and responding party respectfully submits that the facts at hand are easily distinguishable from the high profile instances where the doctrine has been considered. Importantly, in the case at hand, the criminal and immoral conduct as against the plaintiff by the defendants has only been alleged. The plaintiff's position is that its conduct was neither illegal nor immoral. It damaged its own vehicles and sent them out for repair. This is hardly immoral and was not illegal. There is no foundation in law that would classify its actions as illegal or immoral. In <EM>Zastowny</EM>, on the other hand, the illegality of the party had clearly been established. The plaintiff in that instance had already been incarcerated. In such a scenario, it is clear that without application of the doctrine, an inconsistency would be introduced into the fabric of the law that would compromise the integrity of the justice system. The very fabric of the law and the integrity of the justice system would be left unharmed in the present scenario, where the moving party has only brought forth an unproven allegation of mischief. In fact, if the plaintiff's allegations are proven, there is a very real societal interest in having the defendants face civil justice.</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ex Turpi Causa Argument as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P><P1>50. The <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> argument advanced by Wetzel as the moving party is directly tied to their allegations of criminal mischief. As such, we will apply the <EM>Rules</EM> to these arguments following a discussion of the mischief allegation.</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>B.</EM></N><TI><EM>Aviva's Criminal Mischief</EM></TI>
<P><P1>51. The plaintiff and responding party agrees that Wetzel has correctly set out the offence of mischief by citing Section 430 and Section 429(3) of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM> in paragraphs fifteen (15) and sixteen (16) of the moving factum.</P1>
<P1>Reference: <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 430 and 429(3).</P1>
<P1>52. The plaintiff and responding party disagrees with Wetzel's analysis of the ownership of the vehicles and disagrees with his legal analysis regarding &ldquo;piercing the corporate veil&rdquo;. The plaintiff does, in fact, own the vehicles in question. As such, since it has total interest in the damaged property, the defendants would need to rely on Section 429(3) of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM>. Section 429(3)(b) states that the fact that a person has a total interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence <EM>if he caused the destruction or damage with intent to defraud</EM> (emphasis added). If properly applied to the facts at hand, the allegation of mischief would turn on whether or not the plaintiff had an intention to defraud the defendants. The plaintiff's intent was to see if auto body repair shops behaved honestly, or the extent to which they didn't.</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Mischief and Ex Turpi Causa Argument as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Rule 20</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>53. We will first consider these arguments under Rule 20 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. As outlined, summary judgment will only be granted if the Court is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to a claim or defence. Given the mechanics of the allegations and the unorthodox defences of mischief and <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, the plaintiff and responding party respectfully submits that the necessary findings of fact cannot be made. Granting a summary judgement in this instance, would not achieve a just result, as there are clearly genuine issues requiring a trial.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>54. The fact that there are genuine issues requiring a trial was conceded by Wetzel in his testimony during cross-examination on his affidavit. At page twenty-nine (29) of the transcript there is a discussion on the need to establish a genuine issue for trial. At page thirty (30), line nineteen (19), the defendant was asked to agree that there is a dispute as to whether or not Wetzel's appraisals were deliberately inaccurate. Counsel for the defendant then agreed, from lines twenty-two (22) to twenty-four (24), that there is a dispute between what Wetzel has done and what the plaintiff claims. This is the very root of the claims as against Wetzel. Even if there were a proper legal foundation for the defence of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, which the plaintiff says there isn't, it would require a trial on the facts to determine, among other things, whether an offence was committed by the plaintiff.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Supplementary Responding Motion Record, Tab 1 at pages 29-30.</P1>
<P1>55. If there appears to be a genuine issue requiring trial, which the plaintiff submits that there is, the Court should then determine if the need for a trial can be avoided by invoking Rules 20.04(2.1) and (2.2). Use of these Rules will not be against the interest of justice if they will lead to a fair and just result.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><PARANUM>66</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 1 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>56. Rule 20.04(2.1) stipulates a series of powers that the motion Judge may exercise when hearing a summary judgement motion. These powers may be used, <EM>unless</EM> it is in the interest of justice for such powers to be exercised only at a trial: (1) weighing the evidence; (2) evaluating the credibility of a deponent; and (3) drawing any reasonable inference from the evidence (emphasis added).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 20.04(2.1).</P1>
<P1>57. The plaintiff and responding party respectfully submits that it is in the interest of justice for these powers to be exercised only at a trial. Wetzel has not presented sufficient evidence to support his argument of mischief, which would have to be &ldquo;beyond a reasonable doubt&rdquo;, and therefore the application of <EM>ex turpia causa</EM>. In fact, the parties disagree about who owns the vehicles in question and ownership is a central component of the offence of mischief. Additionally, the parties disagree as to whether Wetzel fraudulently prepared the appraisals in question. Although the suggestion that the plaintiff might not own the vehicles in question is frivolous, and could be decided in the plaintiff's favour on motion, Wetzel's best case is that this, and whether he prepared fraudulent appraisals, are issues for trial.</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Rule 21.01(1)(a)</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>58. The plaintiff has not yet filed its Statement of Defence to Counterclaim as it is currently moving to strike paragraphs from the defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim. Applying the current scenario to Rule 25.05, we may conclude that the pleadings have not yet closed.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 25.05(a).</P1>
<P1>59. The Courts have previously decided that it is not appropriate to move under Rule 21.1(1)(a) to decide a point of law until the pleadings have closed.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. CanadianBroadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC><YEAR>1975</YEAR><CITE>8 O.R. (2d) 55</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 5 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 1274</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 6 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>60. The Courts have decided that Rule 21.01(1)(a) is not designed to answer questions of law where no agreement exists on the material facts which underpin the question of law posed. The question of law posed by Wetzel centers around the federal criminal law offence of mischief and the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>. The plaintiff and responding party disputes facts that are required to conclude that the plaintiff committed an act of mischief. Given the disagreement on material facts as between the parties to this motion, such as ownership of the vehicle, the Court should not invoke Rule 21.01(1)(a) to decide a question of law on this motion.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 6107</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 7 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Rule 21.01(1)(b)</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>61. Wetzel has not attacked any one specific paragraph of the plaintiffs Statement of Claim. The relief being sought is to dismiss and/or strike, either in whole or in part, the plaintiff's claim.</P1>
<P1>62. The plain and obvious test established by the Courts is a very high bar to meet. The plaintiff and responding party submits that the pleadings do not make it plain and obvious that the claim will not be able to succeed.</P1>
<P1>63. The plaintiff's Statement of Claim properly sets out the fraudulent acts of the defendants. Distilled down to its roots, the claim is a very simple one. The plaintiff attempted to have it's damaged property repaired for a fair price. If it had been, there would be no claim. Instead, the plaintiff discovered a series of fraudulent events associated with the appraisals and repair of its property. While there may be some disagreement over the facts pleaded, these disagreements do not satisfy the plain and obvious test. On the contrary, they cry out for a trial. Given the existence of video evidence, and independent expert appraisals, there is most definitely a reasonable prospect that the plaintiff will succeed with its claim.</P1>
<P1>64. The plaintiff and responding party submits that Wetzel has only indirectly addressed the allegations of fraud made in the plaintiffs Statement of Claim. In doing so, the moving party has put forth and relied upon federal criminal law, and the rare doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>. These are novel and arguably improper arguments being made in a civil fraud context. The defendants' reliance on novel concepts further indicates that the plain and obvious test has not been satisfied.</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Rule 21.01(3)(d)</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>65. The high bar of the plain and obvious test also applies to Rule 21.01(3)(d). In the case at bar, the plaintiff has asserted a proper cause of action. The evidence surrounding the claim should not be used to foreclose the action at this stage.</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Piercing the Corporate Veil</EM></TI>
<P><P1>66. The plaintiff and responding party respectfully submits that the moving party's reliance on the argument of piercing the corporate veil is misplaced in law. In order to have the corporate veil pierced, a corporation must first be attempting to hold up the veil. In the case at hand, the plaintiff has openly held that its numbered corporation was an authorized agent of and solely controlled by its members.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Responding Motion Record, Affidavit of Douglas Dunstan at paras 9 and 10<BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> Supplementary Motion Record at Tab 8.</P1>
<P1>67. In support of the moving party's legal analysis on piercing the corporate veil, they cite the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Yaiguaje v. Chevron Corp.</SOC></CASEREF> The case was unique in the sense that the appellants appeared in our Courts due to their inability to enforce their judgment in the United States. Specifically, they appeared in Canadian Courts in an attempt to pierce the corporate veil of Chevron Canada to collect from Chevron Corporation in the United States. In deciding to uphold the corporate separation between Chevron Corp. and Chevron Canada, the Court found that Chevron Canada was incorporated over 50 years ago. There was no allegation of wrongdoing on the part of Chevron Canada and the appellants specifically plead that Chevron Canada had not engaged in any inappropriate conduct. This case is irrelevant in the current context. No authority exists for the proposition that a stranger to a corporation can insist on maintaining a corporate veil when the corporation itself does not rely on it (in this case, to prove ownership of 2 cars).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Yaiguaje v. Chevron Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 472</CITE><PARANUM>74</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 14 of the plaintiffs Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>68. Any potential irregularity that existed in the contracts of insurance in place on the subject automobiles has no bearing on the case at hand. For example, if a complete wreck was towed from a dump yard to the defendant's body shop and it was fraudulently repaired and appraised without any insurance at all, there would be a valid claim for fraud. As a further example, if the vehicles did not have a valid policy of automobile insurance and they were appraised and repaired fraudulently, there would still be a valid claim for the fraud regardless of the invalidity of the insurance in place. None of the defendants are party to an automobile insurance contract with the plaintiff, nor is any party claiming under one. The defendants therefore have no standing to even raise the (automobile) insurance coverage issue.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Piercing the Corporate Veil Arguments as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P><P1>69. Wetzel has attempted to tie the argument of piercing the corporate veil into the clear evidentiary issue of ownership. The plaintiff and moving party disagrees with the analysis, questions its applicability and respectfully submits that the argument does not satisfy the requirements of Rule 20, 21.01(1)(a), 21.01(1)(b) or 21.01(3)(d).</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>C.</EM></N><TI><EM>Aviva's Payout Under Known fraudulent Conditions</EM></TI>
<P><P1>70. The plaintiff and responding party respectfully submits that the case at hand is a civil tort/contract case involving the plaintiff making allegations of fraudulent behaviour as against the defendants. Analysis of contracts that the plaintiff or its numbered company was a party to is not relevant to the core issue of the claim for one overlying reason. The defendants are not privy to any of those contracts.</P1>
<P1>71. Wetzel cites section 233(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> in paragraph twenty-six (26) of his moving factum. That section is specifically designed to protect insurance companies against fraud. In order for that section to apply, it is the insurance company, who is privy to the contract between itself and the insured, who must invoke that section. The Supreme Court of Canada outlined the two exceptions to the doctrine of privity in its decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Fraser River Pile &amp; Dredge Ltd. v. Can-Dive Services Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> Justice Iacobucci provided two factors to consider:</P1>
<P1>(a) did the parties to the contract intend to extend the benefit in question to the third party seeking to rely on the contractual provision'; and (b) Are the activities performed by the third party seeking to rely on the contractual provision the very activities contemplated as coming within the scope of the contract in general, or the provision in particular, again as determined by reference to the intentions of the parties'</P1>
<P1>In the case at hand, the clear answer to these exceptions is no, the defendants were never contemplated as third parties to the contracts (auto insurance policies).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Fraser River Pile &amp; Dredge Ltd. v. Can-Dive Services Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1999] S.C.J. No. 48</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 15 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Aviva's Payout Under Known Fraudulent Conditions as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P><P1>72. There is no legal foundation to this argument. Section 233 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> was created to protect insurance companies against instances of fraud. It would be up to the insurance company to invoke this section of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> and it may not be relied upon by parties who are not privy to the contract. Even if there was an instance of insurance fraud, which the plaintiff and responding party does not agree with, it would be up to the insurance company to activate its rights under the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>73. Given the lack of legal foundation attached to the moving party's provincial insurance law arguments, they cannot be used to invoke the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> that are being relied upon.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Mitigation</EM></TI>
<P><P1>74. The concept of mitigation has no application in the current context. The moving party cites a decision that discusses steps that should be taken to mitigate the loss. This argument is circular as mitigation needs to occur after a loss. The loss being claimed in this instance is the damages that were suffered by way of the defendants' fraudulent actions. The plaintiff had no way of mitigating these losses until they occurred.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Mitigation Argument as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P><P1>75. The moving party's mitigation argument does not relate to any of the Rules upon which it relies. As such, the responding party will not conduct a detailed analysis on each individual rule.</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>D.</EM></N><TI><EM>Aviva's Abuse of the Process of the Court</EM></TI>
<P><P1>76. The relevant Rule to support an argument under this heading is 21.01(3)(d). The high bar of the plain and obvious test applies to this rule. The Courts analysis has largely rested on whether or not a plaintiff has asserted a proper cause of action.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Temilini v. Ontario Provincial Police (Commissioner) (C.A.)</SOC><CITE>73 O.R. (2d) 664</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 10 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>77. The moving party cites the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Toronto (City) v. C.U.P.E. Local 79</SOC></CASEREF> in support of its abuse of process argument. This decision veers from the relevant Rule 21.01(3)(d) as its analysis of a Judges power to prevent abuse of process is centered around the issue of relitigation of a criminal conviction.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Toronto (City) v. C.U.P.E. Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>53</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 16 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Aviva's Abuse of the Process of the Court Argument as Applied to the Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P><P1>78. The applicable test to prove an abuse of process under Rule 21.01(3)(d) is the plain and obvious test. In the case at bar, the plaintiff has asserted a proper cause of action. The Court should not foreclose the action on these grounds.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Oppression Arguments</EM></TI>
<P><P1>79. The moving party alleges that the plaintiff's claim for investigative costs is oppressive in nature. The plaintiff and moving party respectfully submits that this is not the proper forum to litigate the appropriate amount of damages claimed. This argument does not relate to any of the Rules being relied upon in the moving party's motion. Furthermore, the moving party has not been able to point to any authority to prove that the plaintiffs claim is oppressive and thus contrary to a proper pleading. The moving party only applies policy reasons that have been formulated to act in favour of Wetzel in what is a very niche fact scenario.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Civil Entrapment</EM></TI>
<P><P1>80. This allegation does not invoke any of the Rules being relied upon by the moving party. Additionally, there is no authority cited to support the existence of the concept of &ldquo;civil entrapment.&rdquo; Even if civil entrapment was recognized by the Court, which the plaintiff and responding party submits that it has not been, the moving party mischaracterized the elements of entrapment.</P1>
<P1>81. The leading decision on entrapment is <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Mack</SOC></CASEREF>. The Supreme Court of Canada recognized entrapment when: (a) the authorities provide an opportunity to persons to commit an offence without reasonable suspicion or acting mala fides; or (b) having a reasonable suspicion or acting in the course of a bona fide inquiry, they [the authorities] go beyond providing an opportunity and induce the commission of an offence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Mack</SOC><CITE>[1988] 2 S.C.R. 903</CITE><PARANUM>115</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 17 of the plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>82. The case law clearly confines the concept of entrapment to law enforcement authorities. Secondly, even if the Court were to extend this principle into a civil concept, the accused party would need to <EM>go beyond providing an opportunity</EM> and would actually need to induce the commission of the offence. The moving party's factum, at paragraph thirty-one (31) only speaks to the opportunity to commit wrongdoing.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Fraud Arguments</EM></TI>
<P><P1>83. Paragraph thirty-two (32) of the Wetzel defendant's factum argues that Aviva's claim itself may be viewed as being fraudulent. Use of the word &ldquo;may&rdquo; immediately eliminates the use of Rule 20, as the allegation itself concedes that there is a genuine issue requiring a trial. The moving party's fraud arguments would also fail the plain and obvious test required under Rule 21.01.</P1>
<P1>84. The plaintiff and responding party further submits that this is not the proper forum to be making an allegation of fraud unrelated to the Rules being relied upon in the moving party's motion. Wetzel could have included the allegation of fraud in its counterclaim.</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>85. The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully requests that the moving party's request for an Order for the summary dismissal of the plaintiff's claim be denied.</P1>
<P1>86. The plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully requests that the moving party's request for an Order dismissing and/or striking the plaintiff's claim pursuant to Rule 21 be denied.</P1>
<P1>87. Costs of this motion; and</P1>
<P1>88. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellip35; Daniel Reister</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
