<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P><P1>1. A total of three motions are being brought concurrently. All of the parties involved in this action have brought motions. The Defendants 1843538 Ontario Inc. c.o.b. Mississauga Collision Centre, and/or McLaren Collision, Fady Warda and Rony Amanuel Warda (Collectively, &ldquo;the Warda Defendants&rdquo;) are moving under Rule 21.01(1)(a) and 21.01(1)(b) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. The Warda Defendants are seeking the following relief:
<P2>a) An Order, pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(a), disposing of all, or part of this action, brought by Aviva Canada Inc. (&ldquo;the Plaintiff') as against the Warda Defendants;</P2>
<P2>b) Alternatively, an Order, pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(b), striking and/or dismissing Aviva's Statement of Claim on the grounds that it discloses no reasonable cause of action and/or it is an abuse of the Court's process;</P2>
<P2>c) Costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity scale; and</P2>
<P2>d) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P2></P1>
<P1>2. The Plaintiff and the Defendant Michael Wetzel (&ldquo;Wetzel&rdquo;) will also be arguing motions on the return date of March 28, 2019. All three motions were scheduled to be heard on the same date as per the Order of Justice Glustein dated October 12, 2018.</P1>
<P1>3. The Plaintiff is bringing a motion pursuant to Rules 21.01, 25.06 and 25.11 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> to strike paragraphs from both the Warda Defendants' and Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>4. Wetzel is bringing a Summary Judgment Motion pursuant to Rule 20.01(3). Additionally and/or alternatively, Wetzel is moving pursuant to Rules 21.01(1)(a), 21.01(1)(b), and/or 21.01(3)(d) to strike and/or dismiss the Plaintiffs claim either in whole or in part on the basis that it discloses no reasonable cause of action and is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P><P1>5. The statement of facts giving rise to the Warda Defendants' motion is identical to the statement of facts relied upon in the Plaintiff's Factum in support of its motion attacking the Defendants' pleadings. For ease of reference, these facts will be repeated from paragraphs 6 thru 8 herein.</P1>
<P1>6. By Statement of Claim issued on April 23, 2018, the Plaintiff commenced an action to recover damages for fraudulent misrepresentation, breach of duty of honest performance of a contract, unjust enrichment, and conspiracy to commit fraud. Additionally, the Plaintiff sought to recover damages for trespass to property, investigative costs and punitive and exemplary damages.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Aviva Canada Inc.'s Statement of Claim dated April 23, 2018.</P1>
<P1>7. Wetzel delivered his Statement of Defence and Counterclaim on July 16, 2018.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Wetzel Defendant's Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>8. The Warda Defendants delivered their Statement of Defence and Counterclaim on October 15, 2018.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> the Plaintiff's Notice of Motion&mdash;Warda Defendants' Statement of Defence and Counterclaim.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES</TI>
<P><P1>9. <BOLD>Whether the Court should dispose of all or part of the action brought by the Plaintiff as against the Warda Defendants' pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(a).</BOLD> The Plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that it would be improper to strike all or part of the action on these grounds.</P1>
<P1>10. <BOLD>Whether the Court should strike and/or dismiss the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim on the grounds that it discloses no reasonable cause of action and/or it is an abuse of the Court's process pursuant to Rule 21.01(1)(b).</BOLD> The Plaintiff and responding party to this motion respectfully submits that it has disclosed a reasonable cause of action. As such, it would be improper to strike and/or dismiss the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim on these grounds.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;STATEMENT OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule 21.01(1)(a)</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>To Any Party on a Question of Law</EM></TI>
<P><P1>11. A complete analysis of Rule 21.01(1)(a) is also found in the Plaintiffs responding factum to the Wetzel Defendant's motion. This analysis occurs at paragraphs twenty-seven (27) thru thirty-one (31). For ease of reference, the law will be repeated below.</P1>
<P1>12. Rule 21.01(1)(a) allows a party to move before a judge for the determination, before trial, of a question of law raised by a pleading in an action where the determination of the question may dispose of all or part of the action, substantially shorten the trial or result in a substantial saving of costs.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 21.01(1)(a).</P1>
<P1>13. The Court in <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Ontario Hydro</SOC></CASEREF> decided that the &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; test is the relevant test for both subrules (a) and (b) of rule 21.01(1).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Ontario Hydro</SOC><CITE>19 O.R. (3d) 529</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 1 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>14. In addition to the plain and obvious test, the Court has previously considered when it would be appropriate to bring a motion to dispose of a point of law. In <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. CanadianBroadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Lieff, commented on what was then Rule 124, which allowed for a point of law to be set down for a hearing at any time before the trial. Justice Lieff decided that the defendant's proper procedure is to bring a motion for a judgment on the pleadings after the pleadings are complete. This principle was later adopted by the Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. CanadianBroadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC><YEAR>1975</YEAR><CITE>8 O.R. (2d) 55</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 2 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 1274</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 3 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>15. According to Rule 25.05 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, Pleadings in an action are closed when, (a) the plaintiff has delivered a reply to every defence in the action or the time for delivery of a reply has expired.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 25.05(a).</P1>
<P1>16. In <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF>, D.M. Brown J., conducted an analysis of the relevant case law related to Rule 21.01(1)(a) motions. The following general principles were extracted from the case law:
<P2>i. the rule is not designed to answer questions of law where material facts are in dispute or, put another way, where no agreement exists on the material facts which underpin the question of law posed;</P2>
<P2>ii. a party should not use Rule 21 to secure the advice of the court about the soundness of its cause of action or defence by asking the court to assume that the material facts it has pleaded will be proved at trial, thereby asking the court to answer a hypothetical question. However, the hypothetical to be avoided is one where an underpinning of the legal determination sought under Rule 21 might be altered at trial, and the legal determination thus rendered redundant;</P2>
<P2>iii. a defendant should not move for the determination of a question of law involving the applicability of a limitation period...;</P2>
<P2>iv. where the question of law depends on the construction of a contract, the terms of which are unclear and capable of more than one meaning, Rule 21 is not an appropriate device to use to anshwer the question; and</P2>
<P2>v. matters of law which have not been settled fully in the jurisprudence usually should not be disposed of at an interlocutory stage of the proceedings.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 6107</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P2>
<P2>Tab 4 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Mischief Allegations</EM></TI>
<P><P1>17. The Warda Defendants make allegations of the Criminal Code Offence of Mischief, citing Section 430(1) of the Criminal Code.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 430(1).</P1>
<P1>18. In doing so, the Warda Defendants ignore Section 429 (3) of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM>, which considers the effect of having interest in property that is destroyed or damaged. Specifically, the section stipulates that: (a) the fact that a person has a partial interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage; and (b) the fact that a person has total interest in what is destroyed or damaged does not prevent him from being guilty of the offence if he caused the destruction or damage with the intent to defraud.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 429(3).</P1>
<P1>19. In the case at hand, the Plaintiff states in its Statement of Claim that it was the owner of the damaged property. As such, according to Section 429(3) of the <EM>Criminal Code</EM>, for mischief to have occurred, the plaintiff must have had the intention of defrauding the defendant.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Criminal Code</EM> (R.S.C., 1985 c. C-46), Section 429(3).</P1>
<P1>20. The issue of law to be decided based on the allegations of mischief is the applicability of the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>. In the Supreme Court of Canada's decision of <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE></CASEREF>, Justice Rothstein revisited and summarized the leading case on <EM>ex turpi causa in</EM> Canada, <EM>Hall v. Hebert</EM> [1993] S.C.J. No 51, into six (6) principles. The first (1) principle is an understanding that an application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine in the tort context invalidates otherwise valid and enforceable actions in tort. The second (2) principle attempts to recognize the grave consequences of applying the doctrine and cautions that it should only be used &ldquo;in very limited circumstances.&rdquo; The third (3) principle states that the only justification for the application of the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is the preservation of the integrity of the legal system. The fourth (4) principle states that the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine generally does not preclude an award of damages in tort because such awards tend to compensate the plaintiff rather than amount to profit. Finally, principles five (5) and six (6), states that the <EM>ex turpi</EM> doctrine is a defence in a tort action; as a defence, the onus is on the defendant to prove the illegal or immoral conduct that precludes the plaintiff's action.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Columbia v. Zastowny</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 6 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Insurance Act Allegations</EM></TI>
<P><P1>21. The Warda Defendants allege that the Plaintiff violated Section 118 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. Section 118 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> comments on how the violation of law can have an effect on a claim for indemnity. The dispute at hand is not a claim for indemnity under an insurance policy. The section has nothing to do with the issues in this action.</P1>
<P1>22. The Warda Defendants cite the case of <CASEREF><SOC>TD General Insurance Co. and Madinei, Re</SOC></CASEREF> at Paragraph 18 of their factum. This decision of a Financial Services Commission of Ontario arbitrator, on appeal from another FSCO arbitrator, seems to be cited as authority for the principle that the facts of the present case are akin to an insured damaging his or her own vehicle to make a fraudulent accident benefits claim, and, in contradiction to the Warda Defendants case, that insurers can seek repayment of any monies paid out for damages on the basis of fraudulent accident claims. The Plaintiff respectfully submits that the <EM>TD</EM> decision is of no assistance. It is a FSCO decision that dealt with the repayment of statutory accident benefits following a staged collision (by the insured). It does not speak to misrepresentation and fraud outside of the context of statutory accident benefits, which concerns a contract between the insured and the benefits carrier. It also deals specifically and exclusively with fraud by an insured person. As pleaded, this lawsuit is not about insurance or an insurance policy of any kind, nor are any of the parties to the lawsuit insured persons in respect of any of the issues in the lawsuit.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>TD General Insurance Co. and Madinei, Re</SOC><CITE>[2018] O.F.S.C.D. No 114</CITE><PARANUM>2</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 7 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 21.01(1)(a) to the Case at Bar</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>23. The Defendants have each filed a Statement of Defence and Counterclaim. The Plaintiff is currently moving to strike paragraphs from those pleadings. As such, the Plaintiff has not yet filed its own Statement of Defence to the Counterclaim. Applying the current scenario to Rule 25.05, we may conclude that pleadings have not yet closed.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r. 25.05(a).</P1>
<P1>24. The Courts have previously decided that it is not appropriate to move under Rule 21.01(1)(a) to decide a point of law until the pleadings have closed.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Plasmapheresis Centres Ltd. v. CanadianBroadcasting Corp. et al.</SOC><YEAR>1975</YEAR><CITE>8 O.R. (2d) 55</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 2 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 1274</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 3 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>25. The Courts have decided that Rule 21.01(1)(a) is not designed to answer questions of law where no agreement exists on the material facts which underpin the question of law posed. The question of law posed by the Warda Defendants as moving party centers around the federal criminal law offence of mischief, the doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> and provincial insurance law. The Plaintiff and responding party disputes facts that are required to conclude that the Plaintiff committed an act of mischief; and to conclude that the Plaintiff violated provincial insurance law. Given the disagreement on material facts as between the parties to this motion, such as ownership of the vehicle and the applicability of Section 118 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, the Court should not invoke Rule 21.01(1)(a) to decide a question of law on this motion.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v. CUMIS General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 6107</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 4 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Rule 21.01(1)(b)</EM></TI>
<P><P1>26. As was the case with Rule 21.01(1)(a), the Plaintiff provided the Court with a full analysis of Rule 21.01(1)(b) in its responding factum to the Wetzel Defendant's motion. This analysis is found at paragraphs thirty-three (33) thru thirty-eight (38). For ease of reference, the law will be repeated below.</P1>
<P1>27. Rule 21.01(1)(b) allows for a pleading to be struck on the ground that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or defence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01(1)(b).</P1>
<P1>28. Rule 21.01(2) stipulates that no evidence is admissible on a motion under 21.01(1)(b).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01(2).</P1>
<P1>29. The test that is applied to determine whether a pleading discloses a reasonable cause of action or defence is the &ldquo;plain and obvious test.&rdquo; The moving party must show that it is plain, obvious and beyond doubt that the respondent could not succeed in the claim or defence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>30. The power of the Court to strike out claims that have no reasonable prospect of success is a valuable housekeeping measure that is essential to effective and fair litigation. By properly exercising the power to strike, the Court can unclutter the proceeding and weed out the hopeless claims. This ensures that only those claims that have some chance of success go on to a trial.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>31. A motion to strike for failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action or defence proceeds on the basis that the facts pleaded are true, unless they are manifestly incapable of being proven. Additionally, no evidence is permissible on such a motion.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1>
<P1>32. Whether the evidence substantiates the pleaded facts, now or at some future date, is irrelevant to the motion to strike. The judge on the motion to strike cannot consider what evidence adduced in the future might or might not show. To require the judge to do so would be to gut the motion to strike of its logic and ultimately render it useless.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2011] S.C.J. No. 42</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>Tab 8 of the Plaintiff's Book of Authorities</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Application of Rule 21.01(1)(b) to the Case at Bar</UNDER></TI>
<P><P1>33. The Warda Defendants, as moving party, have not attacked any one specific paragraph of the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim. The relief being sought under 21.01(1)(b) is to strike and/or dismiss the Plaintiff's entire claim on the grounds that it discloses no reasonable cause of action and/or is an abuse of the Court's process.</P1>
<P1>34. The Plaintiff and responding party agrees that 21.01(1)(b) is the proper rule to move under to strike out a pleading. However, Rule 21.01(1)(b) is not the proper avenue to seek relief for an action being an abuse of the Court's process.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990 194 r 21.01.</P1>
<P1>35. The plain and obvious test established by the Courts is a very high bar to meet. The responding party submits that the pleadings do not make it plain and obvious that its claim will not be able to succeed.</P1>
<P1>36. In the case at bar, the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim properly sets out the fraudulent acts of the defendants. Distilled down to its roots, the claim is a very simple one. The Plaintiff attempted to have it's damaged property repaired for a fair price. If it had been, there would be no claim. Instead, the Plaintiff discovered a series of fraudulent events associated with the appraisals and repair of its property. While there may be some disagreement over the facts pleaded, such as the ownership of the vehicle, these disagreements do not satisfy the plain and obvious test. On the contrary, they cry out for a trial. Given the existence of video evidence, and independent expert appraisals, there is most definitely a reasonable prospect that the plaintiff will succeed with its claim.</P1>
<P1>37. The Plaintiff and responding party submits that the moving Warda Defendants have only indirectly addressed the allegations of fraud made in the plaintiff's Statement of Claim. In doing so, the moving parties have put forth and relied upon federal criminal law, the rare doctrine of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM> and provincial insurance law. These are novel and arguably improper arguments being made in a civil fraud context. The Defendants' reliance on novel concepts further indicates that the plain and obvious test has not been satisfied.</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>38. The Plaintiff / responding party to this motion respectfully requests that the Court refuses to grant the Orders sought by the Warda Defendants under Rule 21.01(1)(a) and (b);</P1>
<P1>39. Costs of the motion; and</P1>
<P1>40. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellip35; Daniel Reisler</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
